## CHAPTER 7: INVESTING IN LIGHT OF THE BIG CYCLE

### Dalio's Investment Philosophy

> **The game I play for handling both my life and my career is to try to figure out how the world works, develop principles for dealing with it well, and then place my bets.** The research that I'm sharing with you in this book was done for that purpose. Naturally, when I look at all that we've covered up to this point, I think about how it applies to my investing. For me to be comfortable that I am doing that well, I need to know how my approach would have worked through time. If I can't confidently explain what happened in the past, or at least have a strategy for dealing with it in light of what I don't know, I consider myself dangerously negligent.

**From studying last 500 years:**
- Big Cycles of great accumulations and great losses of wealth and power
- Of these, **greatest contentious factor was the debt and capital markets cycle**
- From investor's perspective: **Big Investing Cycle**
- Needed to understand cycles well enough to **tactically move or diversify portfolio** to be protected and/or profit
- By understanding them and ideally realizing where countries are in cycles, can do that

**Over ~50 years as global macro investor:**
- Discovered many **timeless and universal truths** that form principles for investing
- Won't get deeply into all here, but will discuss most in next book (*Principles: Economics and Investing*)
- Will convey one important principle now

### Four Market Determinants

> **All markets are primarily driven by just four determinants: growth, inflation, risk premiums, and discount rates.**

- All investments are exchanges of lump-sum payments today for future payments
- Future cash payments determined by growth and inflation
- Risk investors willing to take compared to having cash in hand = risk premium
- What future payments worth today = "present value" determined by discount rate

### How Determinants Drive Returns

> **How these four determinants change drives how investment returns change.**

- Tell me what each determinant is going to do → can tell you what investments will do
- **Knowing this tells me how to connect what is happening in world to what is happening in markets** and vice versa
- Shows me how to balance investments so portfolio doesn't have bias to any environment = good diversification

### Government Influence Through Fiscal and Monetary Policy

> **Governments influence these factors through their fiscal and monetary policies. As a result, interactions between what governments want to happen and what is actually happening are what drive the cycles.**

**Example**: When growth and inflation too low:
- Central banks create more money and credit growth
- Creates buying power
- Causes economic growth to pick up at first, then with lag, inflation picks up
- When central banks constrain money/credit growth, opposite happens: economic growth and inflation both slow down

### Central Governments vs. Central Banks

> **There is a difference between what central governments and central banks do in order to drive market returns and economic conditions. Central governments determine where the money they use comes from and goes to because they can tax and spend, but they can't create money and credit. Central banks on the other hand can create money and credit but can't determine what the money and credit go into in the real economy.**

- Actions from central governments and central banks influence purchases/sales of goods, services, investment assets
- Drives prices up or down

### Building Blocks Approach

> **To me each investment asset reflects these drivers in its own way that is logical in light of the effects on its future cash flows. Each investment asset is a building block for a portfolio, and the challenge is to put together a portfolio well in light of these things.**

**Example**: When growth stronger than expected, all else equal, stock prices likely rise; when growth and inflation higher than expected, bond prices likely fall

> **My goal is to put these building blocks together in a portfolio that is well-diversified and tactically tilted based on what is happening or is going to happen in the world that is affecting these four drivers.**

- Building blocks broken down by country, by environmental bias, all the way down to individual sectors and companies
- When concept put into well-balanced portfolio, looks like 3D graphic showing:
  - Individual Sectors (US, Japan, Equities, Credit, Emerging)
  - Higher Growth Assets
  - Rising Inflation Assets
  - Lower Growth Assets
  - Falling Inflation Assets
  - Risk Premiums & Discount Rates

### Dalio's Unique Approach

> **I understand that my approach is different** from that of most investors for two reasons:

1. **Most investors don't look for historically analogous periods** because they think history and old investment returns largely irrelevant
2. **They don't look at investment returns through the lens** (four determinants framework) Dalio described

- Believes these perspectives give him and Bridgewater competitive advantage
- Up to reader to take or leave them as they like

### The Survivorship Bias Problem

Most investors base expectations on what they experienced in lifetimes, some look back to 1950s or 1960s

- **No investors Dalio knows and no senior economic policy makers he knows** — and he knows many and knows the best — **have any excellent understandings of what happened in the past and why**
- Most investors who look at longer-term returns look at US and UK (countries that won WWI and WWII) as representative
- **That is survivorship bias**
- **Not many stock and bond markets survived WWII**
- These countries and time periods not representative of their past censorship bias

**In looking at returns of US and UK:**
- Looking at uniquely blessed countries in uniquely peaceful and productive time = **best part of the Big Cycle**
- Not looking at what happened in other countries and times before = distorted perspective

**Extending perspective just a few decades back to different places:**
- Get shockingly different perspective
- Will show this because believes reader should have it

### The 35 Years Before 1945

**In 35 years before 1945:**
- **Virtually all wealth destroyed or confiscated** in most countries
- In some countries **many capitalists killed or imprisoned** due to anger at them when capital markets and capitalism failed along with other aspects of old order

**Looking at past few centuries:**
- Such extreme boom/bust cycles happened regularly
- Regular cycles of capital and capitalist boom periods (Second Industrial Revolution, Gilded Age in late 19th/early 20th centuries)
- Followed by transition periods (1900-10 period of rising internal and international conflict over wealth and power)
- Led to great conflict and economic bust periods (similar to 1910-1945)

**Cause/effect relationships behind movements:**
- Now more aligned with **late-cycle bust and restructuring periods** than early-cycle boom and building periods

> **My goal was simply to see and try to understand what happened in the past and do a good job of showing it to you.**

Will start in 1350, though story begins long before

<!-- pp. 221-240 -->

## Historical Investment Catastrophes Across Countries

### Worst-Case Portfolio Losses by Country

- **US, Canada, and Australia** were the only major countries that didn't experience sustained periods of complete portfolio losses (60/40 stock/bond)
- Seven of ten countries saw their wealth completely wiped out (-100% returns) over 20-year windows
- **Russia 1900-1918**: -100% real returns — Russian Civil War ended with communist rule, debt repudiation, destruction of financial markets
- **China 1930-1950**: -100% — asset markets closed during WWII, destroyed when communist rule took hold late 1940s
- **Germany 1903-1923**: -100% — Weimar Republic hyperinflation collapse
- **Japan 1928-1948**: -96% — markets and currency collapsed as markets reopened post-WWII, inflation soared
- **Austria 1903-1923**: -95% — similar to Weimar Germany, hyperinflation led to poor asset returns post-WWI
- **France 1930-1950**: -93% — Great Depression, WWII, German occupation led to poor returns and high inflation
- **Italy** had multiple catastrophic periods: 1928-1948 (-87%), 1907-1927 (-84%, post-WWI depression/inflation helped lead to Mussolini's rise), 1960-1980 (-72%)
- **India 1955-1975**: -66% — post-independence, series of major droughts caused weak economic growth and high inflation
- **Spain 1962-1982**: -59% — post-Franco transition to democracy coupled with inflationary 1970s strained economy

> "The US, Canada, and Australia were the only countries that didn't experience sustained periods of losses."

### Wealth Confiscation, Capital Controls, and Market Closures

- **Wealth confiscation** table shows extensive seizure of private assets across major countries
- Most severe cases occurred during periods of large wealth gaps and internal conflict over wealth when economic conditions deteriorated and/or war occurred
- **Capital controls** were imposed repeatedly: UK (1900, 1920, 1940, 1960), USA (1900, 1920), China (1940, 1960, 1980), Germany (1900, 1920, 1940, 1960), Russia (1900, 1920, 1940, 1960, 1980, 2000)
- **Stock market closures** were common during wartime; communist countries shut markets for a generation
- Chart shows share of major countries shutting stock markets — peaks around WWI, WWII, Fall of USSR/reopening of China's equity markets, and brief spike after 9/11

### Deaths from Violent Conflicts

- Chart shows deaths as percentage of population from internal and external conflicts
- **Germany**: 9% (1930s), 15% (1940s) — highest death rates shown
- **Russia**: 10% (1930s), 13% (1940s)
- **China**: peaks of 2-3% during 1920s-1960s
- **Japan**: 4% (1940s)
- Periods of internal and external fighting over wealth and power led to many deaths

### The Difficulty of Foreseeing Catastrophe

Dalio reflects on how impossible WWI would have been to predict confidently even for those seeing warning signs:

- In early 1900s, looking back over previous decades showed plenty of reasons for optimism based on second half of 19th century
- **50 years before WWI** saw almost no conflict between world's major powers, greatest innovation and productivity growth rates ever, enormous wealth and prosperity
- **Globalization** at new highs — global exports up several multiples in 50 years before WWI
- US, France, Germany, Japan, Austria-Hungary were rapidly rising empires with dizzying technological advancement
- UK still dominant global power, Russia rapidly industrializing
- Only China obviously in decline among countries shown in worst investor experiences table
- **Strong alliances** among European powers seen as means of keeping peace and maintaining balance of power
- Going into 1900, things looked great except wealth gaps and resentments were increasing and debts had become large
- Between 1900 and 1914, conditions worsened and international tensions increased

## Beyond Market Returns: The Full Cost of Crisis

### Wealth Confiscations and Capital Controls

- Beyond terrible returns, impacts of **wealth confiscations, confiscatory taxes, capital controls, and markets being closed** were enormous
- Most investors today don't know of such things and consider them implausible because they haven't seen them in past few decades
- Tables show in which decades these events occurred
- Most severe wealth confiscation came during periods with large wealth gaps and internal conflict over wealth when economic conditions deteriorated/war occurred

### Market Timing and Tax Headwinds for US Investors

Even for lucky investors in winning countries (US — "twice the biggest winner"), two further headwinds existed:

**1. Market Timing:**
- Most investors sell near lows (need money, tend to panic) and buy near highs (have money, drawn into euphoria)
- Actual returns worse than market returns shown
- Recent study: **US investors underperformed US stocks by around 1.5% per year between 2000-2020**

**2. Taxes:**
- Table estimates average impact of taxes for investors in S&P 500 over all 20-year periods (using average tax rates for top quintile today throughout analysis)
- Different implementations: tax-deferred retirement account (401k), holding physical equities and reinvesting dividends annually in brokerage account
- All show significant impact, especially in real returns where taxes erode substantial portion
- **US investors lost about a quarter of their real equity returns on average to taxes in any given 20-year period**
- Pre-tax average annual total return: 9.5%
- Post-tax 401(k): 8.2%
- Post-tax brokerage: 7.9%
- Tax drag on real returns: -20% to -26% depending on account type

## Reviewing the Big Capital Markets Cycle

### The Debt Cycle Mechanics

**In the upwave:**
- Debt increased and financial wealth/obligations rise relative to tangible wealth
- Promises to pay in the future (values of cash, bonds, stocks) can't be met
- Causes "run on the bank"-type debt problems to emerge
- Leads to printing money to relieve problems of debt defaults and falling stock market prices
- Leads to devaluation of money, which causes financial wealth to go down relative to real wealth
- Real (inflation-adjusted) value of financial assets returns to being low relative to tangible wealth
- Then the cycle begins again

> "In the upwave, debt is increased and financial wealth and obligations rise relative to tangible wealth to the point that these promises to pay in the future (i.e., the values of cash, bonds, and stocks) can't be met."

**The anti-capital, anti-capitalist part** of the cycle continues until opposite extreme is reached, then reverses — when peace and prosperity return, cycle goes into up phase, financial assets have excellent real returns

### Two Key Charts Showing the Cycle

**First chart:** Value of total financial assets relative to total value of real assets (i.e., money vs. cash) — uses US numbers since they're most continuous since 1900

**Second chart:** Real return of bills vs. CPI for USA, GBR, DEU, FRA, ITA, JPN, CHE, ESP, NLD

> "When there is a lot of financial wealth relative to real wealth it reverses and real returns of financial wealth, especially cash and debt assets (like bonds), are bad."

- Interest rates and returns for debt holders have to be low and bad to provide relief to debtors with too much debt and to stimulate more debt growth as way of stimulating economy
- Classic late-cycle part of long-term debt cycle
- Occurs when printing more money used to reduce debt burdens and new debts created to increase purchasing power
- Devalues currency relative to other storeholds of wealth and goods/services

> "Eventually as the value of financial assets declines until they become cheap relative to real assets, the opposite extreme is reached and reverses, which is when peace and prosperity return, the cycle goes into its up phase, and financial assets have excellent real returns."

**USA Financial Assets Share of Total Assets chart** shows:
- 1929 stock market bubble
- FDR devaluation
- Nifty Fifty bubble
- WWII
- 1970s devaluation
- Volcker tightening/Reagan Revolution
- Dot-com bubble
- Housing bubble

**Real Return of Bills (vs CPI) chart** shows wild swings across countries, with major negative periods and positive periods cycling

### Hard Assets vs. Cash During Devaluation

> "During periods of the devaluation of money, hard money and hard assets rise in value relative to cash."

**Gold returns during 60/40 drawdowns chart** shows:
- Periods when classic 60/40 stock/bond portfolio declined were periods when gold prices rose
- Not making judgment about gold as investment, simply describing economic and market mechanics from past movements

### The Critical Question for Investors

> "One of the most important questions investors need to regularly ask themselves is whether the amount of interest that is being paid more than makes up for the devaluation risk they face."

### How the Cycle Works in Practice

Classic big debt/money/capital markets cycle repeats through time and across places, reflected in:
1. Relative values of real/tangible money and real/tangible wealth
2. Financial money and financial wealth

- Financial money and financial wealth valuable only to extent they get you real money and real wealth with intrinsic value
- In rising phases, amounts of financial money and financial wealth (created debt/equity assets) increased relative to real money and real wealth they are claims on
- Increased because: a) profitable for capitalists creating/selling financial assets, b) increasing money/credit/capital market assets effective way for policymakers to create prosperity (funds demand), c) creates illusion people wealthier because stated values of financial investments go up when value of money/debt assets goes down
- Central governments and central bankers always created many more claims on real money and real wealth than could ever be turned in for real wealth and real money

**In the rising parts of cycle:**
- Stocks, bonds, other investment assets go up as interest rates go down (falling interest rates make asset prices rise)
- Putting more money in system raises demand for financial assets, lowers risk premiums
- When investments go up due to lower interest rates and more money, makes them seem more attractive at same time interest rates and future expected returns are going down
- More outstanding claims relative to what there are claims on creates more risk
- Should be compensated by higher interest rate, but typically isn't because conditions seem good and memories of debt/capital market crises have faded

### Interest Rate Charts Back to 1900

Four charts show real and nominal bond yields and cash rates for US, Europe, Japan from 1900:

**Real and nominal bond yields:**
- At time of writing, near lowest ever
- Real yields of reserve currency sovereign bonds near lowest ever
- Nominal bond yields around 0%, also near lowest ever

**Real and nominal cash rates:**
- Real yields of cash even lower, though not as negative as 1930-45 and 1915-20 great monetization periods
- Nominal cash yields near lowest ever

Charts marked "Near lowest ever" at time of Dalio's writing

### What This Means for Current Investors

As of this writing, if you invest by giving lump-sum payment for payments in future:

- **US bonds**: wait roughly 45 years to get $100 back then start collecting reward
- **Japanese bonds**: wait 150 years to get money back
- **Chinese bonds**: wait 30 years to get money back
- **European bonds**: likely getting low or nil nominal returns, would likely never get money back given negative nominal interest rates

- Must take inflation into consideration when storing buying power
- At time of writing, in US and Europe may never get buying power back (in Japan takes over 250 years)
- With negative real interest rates, almost guaranteed to have lot less buying power in future

> "Rather than get paid less than inflation, why not instead buy stuff—any stuff—that will equal inflation or better?"

- Dalio sees many investments expected to do significantly better than inflation
- Charts show payback periods for holding cash and bonds in US, both nominal and real terms
- **Longest ever and obviously ridiculous amount of time** at time of writing

## Conclusion

### The Big Cycle from Investor's Perspective

Looking globally back 500 years and in China back 1,400 years: **same cycles occur repeatedly for basically the same reasons**

### Historical Context of Terrible Periods

Terrible periods in years prior to 1945 establishment of new world order are typical of late Big Cycle transition stage when revolutionary changes and restructurings occur:

- While terrible, they were more than matched by terrific upswings that came after painful transition from old order to new order
- Because these things happened many times before, and because can't say for sure what will happen in future, can't invest without having protections against these sorts of things happening and being wrong

---

**Footnote 1:** Discount rate = interest rate used to assess what amount of money in future is worth today. To calculate, one compares where amount of money today, invested at that interest rate (i.e., discount rate), would be worth a certain amount at specific time in future.

**Footnote 2:** If governments and their systems break down, non-government-directed forces take over, which is whole other story won't get into now.

**Footnote 3:** Can see this kind of alchemy at work today in form of digital currency.

**Footnote 4:** When compounded over decade, gains greater than losses because keep building off gains; whereas as approach zero, future percent losses matter less in dollar terms. Comparison of annualizing gains vs. losses represents compounding from 10% annualized gains and -5% annualized losses on average. At more extreme changes multipliers change from there.

**Footnote 5:** For China and Russia, bond data pre-1950 modeled using hard currency bond returns held as though hedged back to local currency by bank or bonds modeled as full default at time of revolution. Annualized returns assume full 10-year period even if markets closed during decade.

**Footnote 6:** Cases of poor asset returns in smaller countries (Belgium, Greece, New Zealand, Norway, Sweden, Switzerland, across emerging world) excluded from this table. For conciseness, worst 20-year window shown for each country/time period (i.e., including Germany in 1903-23 precludes including Germany from 1915-35). For 60/40 portfolios, assumed monthly rebalancing across 20-year window.

**Footnote 7:** While diagram not exhaustive, includes instances where could find clear evidence of each occurring in 20-year period. Wealth confiscation defined as extensive seizure of private assets, including large-scale forced, non-economic sales by government (or revolutionaries in case of revolution). Relevant capital controls defined as meaningful restrictions on investors moving money to/from other countries and assets (though doesn't include targeted measures directed only at single countries, such as sanctions).

**Footnote 8:** Tax impact for 401(k) method applies 26% income tax rate (effective average federal tax rate for top quintile from Congressional Budget Office as of 2017) at conclusion of each 20-year investment period (i.e., tax-free investment growth). Tax impact for brokerage method separately taxes dividends (at same 26% income tax rate) and capital gains, paying taxes on all capital gains (at 20% rate) from both principal and dividend reinvestment at conclusion of each 20-year investment period and netting losses against any gains.

**Footnote 9:** Based on August 2021 levels of 30-year nominal bond yields (treated as perpetuity).

