## Part II: How the World Has Worked Over the Last 500 Years

## Chapter 8: The Last 500 Years in a Tiny Nutshell

Part I described how the perpetual-motion machine works. Part II will show what this machine has produced over last 500 years of history. This chapter sets stage for remaining chapters covering how Big Cycle played out in Dutch, British, American, and Chinese cases. Part III will attempt to squint into future. But first, need to go back to 1500 to get better picture of what world was like when this story begins.

### The World in 1500

World was very different in 1500 yet operated same way it does now — things evolved with evolutionary uptrends producing advancements and big cycles creating swings and bumps around uptrends.

**Key differences in 1500:**

**The World Was Much "Bigger" Then:**
- 500 years ago could travel ~25 miles/day on horseback
- Today possible to travel to other side of world in same time
- Apollo astronauts traveled to moon/back much faster than traveler from Paris to Rome in 1500
- Geographic areas of relevance much smaller, world seemed much bigger
- Europe was one world, Russia another, China and areas around it even more remote world
- States that in retrospect seem tiny and numerous didn't seem that way at time
- Because national boundaries didn't exist as today, almost constant fights with neighbors over wealth and power in neighborhoods

**Countries Didn't Exist—Instead, Territories Were Run by Families:**
- In 1500, no sovereign states with borders and ruling orders
- Instead: **big family estates called kingdoms and dynasties run by kings and emperors that almost constantly fought with their neighbors for wealth and power**
- When kingdom conquered, grew, encompassed enough area, called empire
- Because ruling order centered around families, kingdoms/dynasties could inherit other lands if rulers died with no closer relative
- Like inheriting property or family company today
- Arranged marriages logical way for empire to stay in hands of tighter family group rather than branching off and dissipating over generations

**Religions and Religious Leaders Were Much More Powerful—and Science Didn't Exist:**
- In most of world, elites consisted of monarchs (who supposedly gained power from divine), clergy (represented divine), landowning nobles (oversaw peasants, largely treated them like oxen working land)
- Monarchs had ministers, bureaucracies, militaries that controlled and defended territories

Though Europeans and Chinese on opposite sides of world with virtually no contact, they operated essentially same way, though China's institutions were bigger, more developed, less religious than Europe's.

**The World Was Much Less Egalitarian:**
- Ideas that a) all people should be treated equally and b) judged by people didn't exist at time
- True both within kingdoms and between them
- Power through arms and violence ruled the day
- Up until 1300s-1400s, **serfdom** (peasants essentially treated as property of rulers) existed in most of Western Europe
- Only way for most people to assert power was through revolt
- While this largely changed by 1500, rights afforded to common people remained weak until Enlightenment in 1700s

### The World's Empires in 1500

**Europe:**

- **Habsburg family dynasty** controlled Spain and all territories Spain controlled plus collection of territories forming Holy Roman Empire — included parts of what we now call Netherlands, Belgium, Italy, Germany, Austria. Western world's most powerful empire.

- **Valois (later Bourbon) family dynasty**, main rival to Habsburgs, controlled France — led to lot of fighting between families

- **Tudor dynasty controlled England**, not yet important force in Europe though growing in strength

- **Florence, Venice, and Milan, frequently run as republics with prominent families**, were where action was — most financial, commercial, intellectual, artistic innovation coming out of Europe in 1500 originated in these states. Very rich, played central role in shaping Europe and Western world at this time and for centuries to come because of revolutionary ideas they fostered

- **Papal States run by pope and Catholic Church** — throughout Christian Europe, relationships between monarchs, nobles, and church followed typical formula of elites working in mutually supportive ways to drive ruling orders to their benefit. Church acquired vast wealth, mostly from poor peasants who gave money to church (through system of tithes) and worked without pay on church agricultural lands

- **Rurik dynasty, later Romanovs, ruled Russia**, peripheral power at time, seemed remote to Europeans

- **Ottoman Empire, named after ruling family**, centered in Constantinople, which it conquered in 1453

**Additionally, hundreds, perhaps thousands, of family-run states across Europe** — fought all the time because each had to constantly defend and fight neighbors. Allies and enemies always important and constantly changing. Map shows major powers in Europe 1550 — many more small states couldn't fit on map.

**Asia:**

**The Ming Dynasty** controlled almost all of China and was **most advanced and powerful empire in world**. Like European empires, family-controlled with emperor who had "mandate of heaven." Emperor oversaw bureaucracy run and protected by ministers and military leaders who worked in symbiotic—though sometimes contentious—relationships with landowning noble families who oversaw peasant workers. **In 1500 the Ming Dynasty was approaching its peak and was leaps and bounds ahead of Europe in wealth, technology, and power. Had enormous cultural and political influence all over East Asia and Japan.**

- At time, **Confucian scholars** near top of social hierarchy, which helped them get ahead in politics
- To get ahead, needed to study Confucianism in depth and pass highly competitive exams
- Political decisions frequently based on ruler's interpretations of Confucian ideals
- **"Neo-Confucianism,"** dominant at time, shifted focus of belief system toward more rational, philosophical, academic, and humanistic form
- This practical, evidence-based, scientific thinking key reason China pulled so far ahead of Europe in Middle Ages
- At time, scholars and scientists had significant power, led to remarkable technological advances (gun powder, printing press, architecture, and more)
- Literacy rates extremely high relative to other places at time
- China advanced in medicine — widespread program fighting smallpox infection via early form of vaccination, centuries before Europe
- Financial system relatively well developed with early forms of corporations and banks, history of using (and misusing) printed money, relatively sophisticated financial markets
- Militarily very strong — Ming Dynasty had largest navy in world and standing army of million troops

In his wonderful book, *The Rise and Fall of the Great Powers*, historian **Paul Kennedy** described it well:

> "Of all the civilizations of premodern times, none appeared more advanced, none felt more superior than that of China. Its considerable population, 100–130 million compared with Europe's 50–55 million in the fifteenth century; its remarkable culture; its exceedingly fertile and irrigated plains, linked by a splendid canal system since the eleventh century; and its unified, hierarchic administration run by a well-educated Confucian bureaucracy had given a coherence and sophistication to Chinese society which was the envy of foreign visitors."

> "Ironically and typically, the enormity of the Ming Dynasty's wealth and power is one possible explanation of what eventually led to its fall. Believing that they did not need anything else, the emperors put an end to China's exploration of the world, closed its doors, and retired to lives of pleasure, and turned over the running of government to their ministers and eunuchs, which led to dysfunctional infighting, corruption, weakness, and vulnerability to attack."

There was shift away from pragmatic scientific study and innovation toward pedantic scholarship. As we'll see in Chapter 12, this helped drive decline of China relative to Europe.

<!-- pp. 241-260 -->

## Chapter 8: What Has Happened Since 1500 (continued)

### Global Landscape in 1500

- **Asia fragmented**: India divided among several kingdoms including **Delhi Sultanate** and **Hindu Vijayanagara Empire** in the south
- **Mughal Empire** began conquest of India in the 1520s, eventually becoming one of the world's most powerful
- **Japan in 1500 was divided into many entities, experienced civil war, and was isolated** — not a power of note
- **Ottoman Empire** controlled much of Middle East by mid-1500s, with key rival in the new **Safavid dynasty of Persia** (modern-day Iran)
- **The Americas**: Largest empires were **Aztec Empire** centered in Mexico (capital **Tenochtitlán** probably had greater population than any European city) and **Incan Empire** in South America
- European arrival devastated both powers, leading to emergence of new colonies including the seedlings of what would become the United States 276 years later
- **Africa**: Vast continent three times bigger than Europe divided into dozens of kingdoms, often separated by large, sparsely populated areas
- Biggest in 1500 was **Songhai Empire** in West Africa, with reputation as center of trade and Islamic scholarship

> "That was the lay of the land in 1500. The world order was about to change in very big ways."

### What Has Happened Since 1500

- **Most important changes were the changes in thinking that led to people changing behaviors, particularly about how wealth and power should be shared**
- Biggest periods of change are called "revolutions" and "ages"
- Two key patterns emerge over 500 years:
  1. Several revolutions in ways of thinking led to tremendous evolution and progress over hundreds of years
  2. Many cycles of peaceful/prosperous periods alternating with depressions and wars that marked the ends of old orders and beginnings of new ones

### The Commercial Revolution (1100s–1500s)

- Evolution from solely agriculture-based economy to one including trade in variety of goods
- Began in 12th century, by 1500 centered in **Italian city-states**
- Two factors enabled Italian city-states to become wealthy:
  1. Wars between Christian Europe and Ottoman Empire slowed land trade for spices/luxuries, creating opening for maritime trade
  2. Italian city-states developed **republican governments** modeled after Roman Republic — more inventive and responsive than rest of Europe

#### Venice as Prime Example

- **Venice's governance system** designed with multiple checks and balances for meritocratic approach
- Leader (the **doge**) did not have right to name successor and was restricted from bringing family members into government
- New doges chosen by vote via committees whose members were sometimes chosen by lot from several hundred aristocratic families
- Italians produced well-functioning **capital markets** supported by advances in **bookkeeping** and impartial institutions to enforce contracts
- Before 1500, borrowing tended to be bilateral deals between wealthy citizens — defaults (or expulsion/execution of creditors) were extremely common
- Merchant class could benefit from well-functioning financial system where savings could be invested productively
- Created financial innovations including **credit markets**

#### Currency and Bond Markets

- Coins minted in Italian city-states, especially **Florence's gold florin**, were of solid value and well-recognized
- Began to be accepted as global currencies
- **Venice established a perpetual bond** early in 12th century with 5% coupon that government would issue or purchase back depending on finances/needs
- Venice's merchants owned the bonds and had significant influence on government — default could only be last resort
- Centuries without defaults gave lenders confidence and created institutions for trading bonds in secondary markets
- **The ability to borrow quickly at reasonable rates was an enormous boon to Venice**
- Venice eventually defaulted after losing series of wars around 1500
- Liquid bond markets caught on elsewhere including Netherlands and UK

### The Renaissance (1300s–1600s)

- **A new way of thinking modeled after the ancient Greeks and Romans started in Italian city-states around 1300 and passed through Europe until the 1600s**
- Renaissance thinkers made big pivot toward using **logical reasoning** instead of divine intention to explain how world works
- Led to dizzyingly fast discoveries in artistic and technological advances in Europe
- Began in city-states of northern Italy where Commercial Revolution had created riches enabling advances in trade, production, and banking enabled by intellectualism and creativity
- **The Renaissance was one of history's greatest cases of a self-reinforcing cycle: peaceful periods in which creativity and commerce reinforce each other to produce an economic boom and great advancements**
- Driving force: people and families like the **Medici**, who were merchants and bankers, not feudal kings
- Used riches to support arts, architecture, and science
- Alongside flourishing in art and architecture were huge advances in science, technology, and business
- **Knowledge and ideas spread rapidly because of the invention of the printing press in the mid-15th century**

#### China's Earlier Innovations

- **Many European Renaissance innovations had already been in place in China for centuries** because Chinese discovered key elements to produce it — printing press, scientific method, meritocratic placements of people in jobs — much earlier
- China's **Neo-Confucianism** was like China's Renaissance — led to more logic- and evidence-based thinking and more inventive rather than religious worldviews
- As new ideas spread across Europe in late 16th and early 17th centuries, luminaries such as **Shakespeare** and **Francis Bacon** in England, **Descartes** in France, and **Erasmus** in the Netherlands had broad impacts
- Living standards rose dramatically, though much more for elites than peasants
- In Italy, period of relative peace and prosperity eventually led to excesses, decadence, and decline as city-states became less competitive and financial conditions deteriorated

### The Age of Exploration and Colonialism (1400s–1700s)

- **Age of Exploration began in the 1400s when Europeans traveled all over the world in search of wealth, creating widespread contact between many different peoples for the first time and beginning to shrink the world**
- Roughly coincided with Renaissance because technological marvels translated into advancements in shipbuilding and navigation
- Riches those ships brought back financed further Renaissance advancements

#### European Explorations

- **Ruling families supported these money-making explorations and split the profits with explorers**
- **Henry the Navigator**, brother of head of Portuguese royal family, sponsored earliest voyages and established trading empire in Africa and Asia
- Spain followed suit, conquering and colonizing significant portions of Western Hemisphere, including precious-metal-rich **Aztec** and **Incan** empires
- Though Portugal and Spain were rivals, the unequal world was huge, and when they had disputes, they were successfully mediated
- Spain's integration into **Habsburg Empire** and control over highly profitable silver mines made it stronger than Portugal in 1500s
- For roughly 60-year period starting in late 1500s, Habsburg king ruled Portugal as well
- Both translated wealth into golden ages of art and technology
- Spanish Empire grew so large it became known as **"the empire on which the sun never sets"** — expression later used to describe British Empire

#### Economic Impact: Spanish Price Revolution

- **As European nations found ways to make their explorations more profitable, the rise of global trade transformed their economies**
- Flow of new riches (particularly silver) to Europe fueled rise in prices for basic goods and services
- Referred to as **Spanish Price Revolution**
- **Europe went from hundreds of years of steady prices to a doubling of prices every few decades, a reminder of how big shifts can have economic impacts that seem unimaginable based on one's most recent experiences**

#### China's Exploration and Pullback

- **China's Ming Dynasty had its own version of the Age of Exploration but abandoned it**
- Starting in early 1400s, **Ming Dynasty Emperor Yongle** empowered his most trusted admiral, **Zheng He**, to lead seven major naval expeditions — "treasure voyages" — around the world
- Though not colonizing expeditions (historians debate extent to which they were commercial), these naval missions helped project China's power abroad
- **Yongle's navy was the largest and most sophisticated in the world**, featuring larger and better-constructed ships than any country in Europe would produce for at least a century
- China's international influence (measured by number of foreign cities engaged in formal tributary relationships with mainland) increased rapidly
- **Ming emperors chose to end these voyages and pulled the empire into itself**
- Remains matter of conjecture whether due to expense of military/naval expeditions or because emperors believed they had all they needed within China so there was no need for exploration
- **The result was an Age of Isolationism in China and in Japan as well, where it was called Sakoku**
- For next several centuries, **China and Japan broadly moved away, in fits and starts, from openness toward foreigners and toward distance and isolation**

### The Reformation (1517–1648)

- **Beginning in the 1500s in Europe, Protestant religious movements initiated a revolution against the Roman Catholic Church, which contributed to a series of wars and the bringing down of the then-existing European order**
- At the time, existing order consisted of monarchs, nobles, and the church in symbiotic relationships
- Reformation took aim at power and corruption of Roman Catholic Church
- Sought independent religion in which people dealt with God directly rather than one mediated by church's rules
- Many Catholic bishops and senior clergy lived like princes in palaces
- Church sold **"indulgences"** (supposed reduction in time people would have to spend in purgatory)
- Roman Catholic Church was a nation as much as it was a religion, directly governing sizable share of modern Italy (the **Papal States**)

#### Martin Luther and Spread

- Reformation started in 1517 when **Martin Luther** published his ***Ninety-Five Theses***, challenging papal monopoly on interpretation of Bible and papal power in general
- When he refused to recant, he was declared a heretic and excommunicated
- His ideas — and those of other theologians — nonetheless took hold in large parts of Europe, thanks to political support of key nobles and new printing press technology
- **That move, together with the usual constant fighting for power, broke down the existing European world order**

#### Wars of Religion

- In virtually all major Christian powers, immediate impact was increased internal conflict and instability
- Instability extended between countries too
- **The Wars of Religion were intertwined with the wars against the existing orders and existing elites**
- **They included an extended civil war in France in which an estimated 3 million people died**
- **Later contributed to an extended civil war in the UK**
- **In the end, the Reformation led to Protestants earning substantial rights and freedoms**
- **It also undermined the power of the Holy Roman Empire and the Habsburgs**
- **Left Germany with deep divisions that would continue to build through the end of the incredibly brutal Thirty Years' War in the mid-1600s, and led to civil wars for over a hundred years**
- **As is typical, the big war led to a new order, which was followed by a period of peace and prosperity**

### The New World Order Following the Thirty Years' War (1648)

- On its surface, Thirty Years' War pitted Protestant countries against Catholic ones
- However, full story was more complicated with wider geopolitical interests related to wealth and power playing a role
- **At the end of the war the new order was laid out at the Peace of Westphalia**
- **Most important breakthroughs: establishment of geographic borders and the sovereign rights of the people within those borders to decide what happens in their domains**
- Like most periods after major wars and establishment of new orders, there was extended time of peace between countries
- **Dutch emerging from the chaos as the leading global economic power**
- However, battles for wealth and power — most importantly between declining monarchies and their subjects — continued across continent

### The Invention of Capitalism (1600s)

- **Beginning with the Dutch, the development of publicly available and popularly used equity markets allowed savers to effectively transfer their buying power to entrepreneurs who could put that buying power to productive and profitable use**
- **This significantly improved the allocation of resources and was stimulative to economies because it produced new buying power**
- **It also produced the capital markets cycles**
- Series of related economic and financial developments — most notably publicly traded stock and bond markets such as opening of **Amsterdam Stock Exchange** in 1602 and **Bank of England's** first government bond issuance (to fund war with France) in 1694
- Along with advances of Scientific Revolution, invention of capitalism was key reason behind shift from slow real GDP growth to faster growth
- Dalio will explore this innovation and tremendous impact in more detail in following chapter

### The Scientific Revolution (1500s–1600s)

- **Scientific Revolution was an extension of the Renaissance-era shift from finding truth in religion to finding truth in logical reasoning and the Reformation's drive to question authority and think for oneself**
- **Led to the development of the scientific method, which improved humanity's understanding of the world, establishing protocols by which scientific discoveries could be investigated and proven and ushering in many discoveries that raised living standards**
- Scientific method pioneered by **Francis Bacon** in early 1600s, though many important advances in astronomy — particularly work of **Copernicus** and **Galileo** — took place earlier, in 1500s
- These discoveries vastly expanded European knowledge about solar system for first time since Greco-Roman period
- Paralleled by many others across anatomy, mathematics, physics (e.g., **Isaac Newton's laws of motion**), and many other fields
- European governments began to support and sponsor this research
- Most famous example: **Royal Society** in UK, founded in 1660 and proved instrumental in promoting exchange of ideas and discoveries
- Newton was its president from 1703 to 1727
- Over centuries to come, discoveries of Scientific Revolution helped unleash economic growth and greater competitiveness for major European powers, particularly UK
- Ideas and methods that underpinned revolution were applied to more and more fields through movement known as the **Enlightenment**

### The First Industrial Revolution (1700s–1800s)

- Beginning in UK in 1700s, freeing people to be inventive and productive and providing them with capital led many societies to shift to new machine-based manufacturing processes
- Creating **first sustained and widespread period of productivity improvement in thousands of years**
- Improvements began with agricultural inventions that increased productivity, led to population boom and secular shift toward urbanization as labor intensity of farming declined
- As people flocked to cities, industry benefited from steadily increasing supply of labor, creating virtuous cycle and leading to shifts in wealth and power both within and between nations
- New urban populations needed new types of goods and services, which required government to get bigger and spend money on housing, sanitation, education, as well as infrastructure for new industrial capitalist system (courts, regulators, central banks)
- **Power moved into the hands of central government bureaucrats and the capitalists who controlled the means of production**
- Geopolitically, these developments most helped UK, which pioneered many of the most important innovations
- UK caught up to Netherlands in output per capita around 1800, before overtaking them in mid-19th century
- **British Empire** approached its peak share of world output (around 20%)

### The Enlightenment and the Age of Revolutions (1600s–1700s)

- **Also known as the Age of Reason, the Enlightenment was essentially the scientific method applied to how humans should behave**
- **This way of thinking became widespread in Europe in the 1700s and 1800s and was an extension of the diminishing of the rights of the monarchy and the church and the increasing of the rights of the individual that characterized earlier intellectual movements**
- New fields like economics expanded thanks to thinkers like **Adam Smith**
- Figures like **John Locke** and **Montesquieu** pushed political philosophy in new directions
- Enlightenment ideas promoted rationality and individual liberties and undermined monarchies and religious powers
- Creating movement toward overthrowing monarchies known as **Age of Revolutions**
- Included American, French, Spanish, German, Portuguese, and Italian revolutions
- As is typical, era of upheaval led some nations to seek out strong leaders who could bring order to chaos
- In case of France, that leader was **Napoleon**, who changed course not just of French history but of European history as he sought to conquer all of Europe
- Napoleon was classic great benevolent dictator who converted chaos into order and prosperity, and expanded empire with his military prowess
- As is often the case, he overreached and failed

### The Napoleonic Wars and the New World Order (1803–1815)

- **Napoleonic Wars lasted from 1803 to 1815, when Great Britain and its allies defeated Napoleon and his allies**
- **As is usual, the victors got together to create a new world order, which was hashed out at the Congress of Vienna**
- Drew boundaries to ensure that no European power would become too dominant, based on **balance of power concepts** that would avoid war
- **The British emerged as the world's leading empire**
- **As is typical after the war and the establishment of a new order, there was an extended period of peace and prosperity — the Pax Britannica**

### Western Powers Move into Asia (1800s)

- **British and other Western powers brought their gunboats to India, China, and Japan in the mid-1700s and into the 1800s, causing dramatic disruptions to the course of their histories**
- **At the time, both China and Japan were isolationist**
- India was controlled by **Mughal Empire**, which had expanded into significant power in South Asia but experienced rapid decline in 1700s
- Western powers significantly more advanced militarily at this time, wanted to force trade on all three
- Chinese attempted to fight the British but lost
- Japanese saw this and opened themselves for trade after **US Commander Matthew Perry** sailed four warships into Tokyo Bay in 1853
- **These developments led to the eventual fall of the Qing Dynasty, the resignation of the Japanese government, and the continued control of India by the British**
- **Especially in Japan and China, it also led to the realization that they needed to modernize, which prompted the Meiji Restoration (in Japan) and the Self-Strengthening Movement (in China)**
- **This move was very successful in Japan and not successful in China, which continued to suffer in what the Chinese call the Century of Humiliation**

### Second Industrial Revolution (1850s–early 1900s)

- Beginning in mid-1800s, second big wave of innovation took place
- Centered at first around steam-powered locomotion (railroads) and then electricity, telephones, interchangeable manufacturing parts, and other innovations at turn of 20th century
- Whereas First Industrial Revolution centered on UK, Second Industrial Revolution primarily benefited United States
- **As is typical, this period produced both great wealth and great wealth gaps and excesses in the capital markets, leading to an era known as the Gilded Age in the US**

### Invention of Communism (1848)

- **The invention and development of communism in the mid-1800s came as a reaction against both capitalism and the wealth gaps it created and the benefits of the Industrial Revolutions going more to the owners of the new technologies than to the workers**
- Conflicts between communists and established powers intensified around turn of century
- Led to major revolutions in 20th century, including in both Russia and China where communist governments took power
- **That brings us to the 20th century, which had two big cycles of boom, busts, wars, and new orders, the second of which we appear to be in the late stages of**
- **Because I review these comprehensively in Chapters 10 through 13, and because they are much more familiar to most readers, I will end this overview here and dive now into the story of the Dutch and how they rose to become the first global reserve currency empire**

<!-- pp. 261-280 -->

## Dutch Rise: Innovation and Capital Markets

### Key Dutch Innovations

- **Dutch East India Company**: world's first mega-corporation, accounting for ~1/3 of global trade
- Dutch openness to new ideas, people, and technology accelerated their rise
- Government increased military investments to protect trade routes and hold off British rivals
- **World's first reserve currency**: Dutch guilder, backed by innovative banking system via **Bank of Amsterdam**

### Economic Success Metrics

- Income per capita rose to 2x+ most European powers during peak
- Heavy investment in education and infrastructure compounded advantages
- Dutch literacy rates: twice the world average
- **Amsterdam became world's most important financial center** with only 1-2 million population
- Dutch produced ~25% of all major world inventions during their peak (shortly before independence from Spain)

> "In short, the Dutch were superbly educated people who were very hardworking and inventive"

### The Two Critical Inventions

1. **Uniquely effective sailing ships** that enabled global reach, combined with military skills from European conflicts
2. **Capitalism** that fueled these endeavors

### The Capital Markets Cycle of the Dutch

**The Dutch invented capitalism as we know it.** Revolutionary but brought potentially deadly consequences.

- Before Dutch innovations, collective public ownership via equity markets **did not exist**
- **Dutch East India Company**: world's first publicly listed company (1602)
- **Amsterdam Stock Exchange**: established August 1602, first stock exchange globally
- Spread share ownership widely (>1 in 50 Dutch adults owned shares)
- Clear rules on ownership and transfer made markets transparent
- **World's first transnational corporation** with modern features: shareholders, corporate logo, board of directors

> Early 1700s peak: Dutch East India Company dividends = nearly $1 of every $100 of total Dutch GDP

- Dutch outcompeted Spanish and Portuguese for Europe-Asia trade, particularly China and Indonesia (highly profitable)

### Banking Innovation: The Bank of Amsterdam

Prior to Dutch banking: chaotic currency situation with ~800 different foreign/domestic coins circulating (many debased or counterfeit), creating uncertainty and slowing trade.

**Bank of Amsterdam (1609)** established as exchange bank to:
- Protect commercial creditors from unreliable commodity money
- Generate monetary stability
- Put Netherlands' coinage and Dutch financial system at center of global finance
- **Bank guilder backed by hard currency = Type 2 money** (first true reserve currency)

**Baltic and Russian trade relied solely on guilders and Bank of Amsterdam bills** for pricing and contract settlement.

The guilder remained effective as both medium of exchange and storeholder of wealth after Bank of Amsterdam founding, with limited debasement maintaining stability.

## The Thirty Years' War and Peace of Westphalia

### The War (1618-48)

Classic balance of power dynamics: fight over wealth and power, extended conflict.

**Alliances:**
- Catholic side: Habsburg Austria, German Catholic territories, Bavaria, Spain, Papal States
- Protestant side: German Protestant nobles, allied with Denmark, Netherlands, Sweden, France at different points

Fighting was about money, religion (Protestants vs Catholics), and geopolitics. **Money and geopolitics mattered more than religious ideologies.**

Example: French monarchy (Catholic, led by **Cardinal Richelieu**) allied with Lutheran Sweden and Calvinist Netherlands.

### The Habsburgs Lost

**Peace of Westphalia** expanded autonomy of individual Holy Roman Empire princes, eroding Austrian emperor authority.

**The deal invented countries as we know them**: allowed sovereignty of the state with ability to make choices within geographic borders (languages, their languages, rules), instituted respect for boundaries. No longer would borderless power grabs occur without starting major war.

- Created concept of states → nationalism → pursuit of national interests
- Reshaped balance of power between rival states
- **Made religious authorities much less powerful**

### "Exhaustion of War" Pattern

**Peace of Westphalia reflected exhaustion of war → long period of peace and prosperity.**

One quarter of Europe's population died from combat, disease, or starvation.

> "Because wars are so much more terrible than even those who are eager for them can imagine, they lead to treaties that redefine the order and are followed by periods of peace, until the next big war happens."

### Dutch Benefits from New Balance of Power

Dutch benefited from relative stability; most importantly, protected from Habsburg domination.

> "Wars are devastating financially; that is true for the winners and much more so for the losers."

France (a "winner") faced widespread rebellions due to financial problems. Habsburg Empire more devastated. **Dutch were less financially hurt** — they benefited from the peace that fostered the Dutch Golden Age. Combined with shipping capabilities and Dutch East India Company, Dutch military and shipping expanded power globally.

## THE TOP

**Dutch Golden Age → shift to "living the good life" → weakened finances.** Other powers rose and challenged them.

**Capitalism + Enlightenment → Industrial Revolution (centered in Britain).** Dutch failed to keep pace with innovation, trade, and wealth in the 1600s. Cost of maintaining declining, overextended empire became unsustainable.

### Classic Reversal Dynamics

At the top, Dutch experienced reversal of classic rise ingredients:

- **Educational and technological edge eroded**
- Dutch became **uncompetitive** generally and via Dutch East India Company decline
- **1700s: Industrial Revolution led British to overtake Dutch as preeminent economic and financial power in Europe**
- Slower growth relative to other powers made empire maintenance difficult (especially for small nation)
- Military conflicts to protect vast wealth left Dutch **overextended and overindebted**
- **Guilder's reserve currency status declined**, deteriorating after Dutch lost war to British
- **Financial center eroded** after debt crises and run on central bank/currency

### Summary of Dutch Wars

Despite Peace of Westphalia stability, Dutch fought to build then hold empire via naval trade wars:

- **Eighty Years' War (1566-1648)**: Protestant Netherlands revolt against Catholic Spain; full independence realized 1648
- **First Anglo-Dutch War (1652-54)**: England's Navigation Act (1651) required American goods carried by English ships; trade war stalemate
- **Dano-Swedish War (1657-60)**: Sweden threatened profitable Baltic routes; Dutch defeated Swedish
- **Second Anglo-Dutch War (1665-67)**: Another trade dispute; Dutch victory
- **Franco-Dutch War (1672-78) and Third Anglo-Dutch War (1672-74)**: Fought over trade; Dutch foiled French conquest plans at tremendous cost
- **Fourth Anglo-Dutch War (1780-84)**: British retaliation for Dutch support of American Revolution; significant Dutch defeat, ending guilder as reserve currency

### The Glorious Revolution (1688) and Dutch Decline

Ironically, **military victory led to power shift away from Netherlands.**

1688: **William III of Orange** married Mary II (daughter of unpopular English king), invaded England, took power (**Glorious Revolution**), creating new internal order for Great Britain.

Short-term benefit for Dutch having William III on British throne, but **second-order consequences of economic integration and military cooperation drove decline of Dutch economic power and guilder over next century.**

Post-1688:
- Dutch merchants shifted operations to London, hastening London's rise as international finance center
- Alliance gave English merchants access to Dutch trade
- William III focused on ruling England, not Netherlands
- 1702: William III died heirless; direct connection broken
- Dutch provinces splintered
- England-Netherlands continued military partnerships against French through mid-1700s, but began competing in same markets

### British Advantages: Industrial Revolution

Mid-18th century: Dutch Empire no longer world's leading empire. **Britain learned from Dutch innovations** and invested in education to strengthen capabilities.

Coupled with capitalism, led to **Industrial Revolution** advancements:
- Standardizing inputs
- Moving production from artisans to factories
- Transformative new inventions

British became more productive, captured more trade, built military might.

### The Wealth Trap

**As Dutch became extremely wealthy, they became less competitive**—wages generally higher than other European parts. Dutch East India Company lost competitive edge (e.g., ineffective trading popular products like tea).

**Dutch economic growth slowed relative to other powers → harder to pay for and maintain vast empire.** Military conflicts to protect wealth left them **overextended**.

From ~1725-1800: financial decline unfolded in classic ways.

**Reserve currency status remained strong even as other powers declined.** Bills of exchange were dominant vehicle for international trade credit; merchants trading with Dutch forced to open Bank of Amsterdam accounts → **~40% of global trade settled in Amsterdam using bank guilders.** This gave Dutch "extraordinary privilege" of getting into lots of debt.

## THE DECLINE

**Around 1750: British (and French) became stronger than Dutch** due to:
- a) Dutch became more indebted
- b) Internal fighting over wealth
- c) Weakened militarily
- **All made them vulnerable to decline and attack**

Wealthy Dutch savers moved cash into British investments (stronger growth, higher yields). Guilder remained widely used as global reserve currency.

> As is typical, a rising great power challenged the existing great power in a war.

### The Fourth Anglo-Dutch War (1770s)

1770s: English began interfering with Dutch shipping, escalating after Dutch traded arms with American Revolution colonies.

**1781: English delivered massive blow to Dutch Navy in Caribbean**, seizing Dutch territories in Caribbean and East Indies.

Dutch East India Company lost half its ships and key trade route access → borrowed heavily from Bank of Amsterdam to survive.

Rival powers grabbed more Dutch shipping business. British blockades in Netherlands and East Indies caused liquidity crisis.

### Classic Bank Run Dynamic

**Financial losses and large debts → classic central bank move to print more money.**

**Bank of Amsterdam printed more paper money (loans to Dutch East India Company) → clear there would not be enough gold/silver to cover all paper claims → classic "run on the bank"** where investors exchanged paper money for precious metals.

Bank's precious metal store exhausted; guilder supply soared even as demand fell.

**Bank of Amsterdam deposits traded at large discounts to guilder coins** (gold/silver). Bank used coin/precious metal holdings (reserves) to buy currency on open market to support deposit value, but lacked adequate foreign currency reserves.

**Accounts backed by coins plummeted from 17 million guilder (March 1780) to 300,000 guilder (January 1783)** as gold/silver coin owners demanded them back.

Bank run marked end of Dutch Empire and guilder as reserve currency.

- 1791: Bank taken over by City of Amsterdam
- 1795: French revolutionary government overthrew Dutch Republic, establishing client state
- 1796: Dutch East India Company nationalized (stock worthless)
- 1799: Dutch East India Company charter expired

### Currency Collapse

Charts show exchange rates between guilder and pound/gold. As bank lost credibility, investors fled to other assets and currencies.

**Guilder remained stable through most of decline era, then:**
- (A) Stable through Golden Age
- (B) Fourth Anglo-Dutch War → money printing, initial pressure on guilder (run on Bank of Amsterdam)
- (C) Brief stabilization as investors sought safe havens at French Revolution start
- (D) French overthrew Dutch; accounts at bank basically wiped out

### Interest Rates and Devaluation

**Interest rates rose and Bank of Amsterdam had to devalue, undermining credibility of guilder as storeholder of wealth.** British pound replaced Dutch guilder as leading reserve currency.

**Classic monetary transition:** Bank of Amsterdam started with **Type 1 monetary system (precious metal) → morphed into Type 2 monetary system (paper money linked to precious metal).** Transition occurred during financial stress and military conflict—risky because decreased currency trust, adding bank-run-like risk.

Bank of Amsterdam deposits = reliable storeholder of wealth for nearly two centuries. Began trading at large discounts to guilder coins (gold/silver). Bank used holdings to buy currency on open market but lacked adequate foreign reserves.

Accounts backed by coins held: 17M guilder (March 1780) → 300K guilder (Jan 1783).

The bank run marked end of Dutch Empire and guilder as reserve currency.

### Dutch East India Company Returns

Chart shows returns by starting investment year. **Like most bubble companies: great at first, seemed to have great fundamentals, attracted more investors even after fundamentals weakened. Ultimately failed fundamentals and excessive debt broke it.**

Returns on declining empire investment fell relative to rising empire returns. British East India Company returns far exceeded Dutch East India Company; Dutch government bond returns terrible relative to British bonds.

### Transition to British Empire

**The decline of Dutch Empire → next Big Cycle: rise and decline of British Empire and its reserve currency.**

The story is basically the same, just a century later in more technologically evolved form with different people/clothes/language.

<!-- pp. 281-300 -->

## Chapter 11: The Big Cycle Rise and Decline of the British Empire and the Pound (continued)

### Britain's Victory Over France and the Post-War Order

- **Britain's rise wasn't complete until the early 1800s** — had one last great rival power to defeat: France, led by **Napoleon**
- **Napoleon** was a fear to conquer Europe and become the greatest power via the **Napoleonic Wars**
- Created the classic great power rivalry and balance of power dynamic described in Chapter 2 addendum
- **Britain won through effective economic as well as military warfare**
- Following the **Big Cycle script**: after wars establishing the dominant power, **new world order set out by winners followed by a long period (100 years) of relative peace and prosperity**
- **British Empire became the greatest empire ever** — at peak, only 2.5% of world population in UK, but produced over 20% of world's income, controlled over 20% of world's land mass and 25% of global population

### The Rise (Starting Around 1600)

#### Political Foundation: Rule of Law Over Monarchy

- Early 17th century: massive conflicts in Europe and Britain radically changed prior orders
- **Thirty Years' War** devastated Europe — war between ideologies, religions, economic classes
- **Peace of Westphalia** created new European order, established countries as we know them, created fractured Europe with different choices in different countries
- Britain's internal turmoil: **English Civil War** (brutal class conflict) and **Glorious Revolution** (William III, Dutch ruler, became king of England)
- Conflicts weakened monarchy, strengthened Parliament
- **English Civil War led to King Charles I being tried and executed**, monarchy replaced by **Commonwealth of England under Oliver Cromwell**
- **Rule of law established rather than rule of monarchy**, creating new balance of power between king and Parliament
- Strong Parliament allowed moderately meritocratic selection of leaders — prime minister had to command Parliament's confidence, not just be royal favorite
- Key statesmen came from merchant families: **William Pitt the Elder, Will Pitt the Younger, Robert Peel, William Gladstone, Benjamin Disraeli**

#### Enlightenment Ideas Shape Britain's Rise

- Revolutionary strengthening of Parliament heavily influenced by **Enlightenment thinking** (late 1600s onward)
- Shaped by **Francis Bacon (1561–1626)**: **human-centric philosophy — society should be based on reason and science, government's power comes from the people, not from God**
- **Debate and skepticism were encouraged**
- **Improvements in basic education (literacy rates rose), dissemination of ideas via printed materials (first encyclopedias and dictionaries printed en masse), growing number of transnational elites created new "public sphere" of political and social thought**
- **Key thinkers produced ideas and concepts still important in the Western world**
- Enlightenment influenced countries differently — from autocratic monarchs (Catherine the Great in Russia) to representative form (America's Founding Fathers)
- **UK reaped benefits of Enlightenment's strong political institutions and rule of law alongside emphasis on science**, which supported major discoveries

#### Financial Strength: Centralized Fiscal Authority

- **British system's respect for rule of law, combined with strong education, gave foundation to gain competitive advantages in commerce and innovations**
- **England became financially strong** — created **powerful and centralized fiscal authority allowing state to raise significantly more revenue than international rivals**
- **By 18th century, tax burden in Britain was almost twice that of France**
- **Bank of England created in 1694** — helped standardize and increase liquidity of UK government debt, improving ability to borrow
- Government bond yields fell drastically (both outright and relative to other countries) over early 1700s
- By early 1700s: classic signs of empire on the rise, Britain's leadership in innovation clear

### The Industrial Revolution

- **Well-educated population + culture of inventiveness + availability of capital** to financially support new ideas gave competitive wave of competitiveness and prosperity
- **England's geological endowments of iron and coal** gave great boost to producing economic transformation: **First Industrial Revolution**
- Shift changed Europe from **primarily rural and agrarian society (most people poor, power with landowners) to urban and industrial society (people as whole got richer, though benefits disproportionately accrued to elites, power resided with central government bureaucrats and capitalists)**
- **Geopolitically, strengths led UK to overtake Dutch as preeminent economic and financial power in Europe around 1750**, 30 years before defeating Dutch militarily

#### Timeline of Key UK Innovations

- 1712: Steam engine invented
- 1719: Silk factory established
- 1733: Flying shuttle (basic weaving machine) invented
- 1764: Spinning jenny (multi-spindle weaving machine) invented
- 1765: Separate condenser (for steam engines) invented
- 1769: Water frame (hydraulic power for weaving machines) invented; steam engine upgraded
- 1785: Power loom invented; iron refining developed
- 1801: Steam-powered locomotive on wheels invented
- 1816: Steam-powered locomotive on rail patented
- 1825: Railway construction initiated connecting Manchester and Liverpool

#### Productivity Revolution and Economic Dominance

- Revolutionary changes made Europe urban and industrial, with goods made by machines in city factories
- New urban population required new goods and services, government got bigger, spent money on housing, sanitation, education, infrastructure (courts, regulators, central banks)
- **Power in hands of central government bureaucrats and capitalists who controlled means of production**
- **United Kingdom pioneered most important innovations and used new methods to pull ahead, becoming world's leading superpower**
- UK's living standards caught up to Netherlands by around 1800, overtook them mid-19th century
- UK approached zenith of share of world output (around 20%)
- UK became world's dominant trading nation (late 1700s), maintained position through 19th century
- Acceleration in output across all countries through most of 1800s
- Most countries in Stages 3 and 4 of internal order cycle

#### Military and Financial Power

- **UK's military strength — especially navy — helped establish colonies and take over those of other European powers, secured control over global trade routes**
- **Profitability of empire more than paid for military spending** because it supported economic activities
- Thanks to **Bank of England's financial innovations** and guilder's collapse, **London became world's financial center, pound sterling became world's reserve currency**
- **Great Britain followed classic Big Cycle steps of rising empire**

#### Trade with China Sets Stage for Conflict

- Britain took Netherlands' mantle as top trader with China
- Industrial Revolution meant Europe no longer demanded luxury manufactured goods from China, instead sought commodity: **tea**
- China wasn't interested in European goods, continued seeking payment in precious metals
- Sowed seeds of **great British-Chinese conflict** leading to **Opium Wars** and **China's Century of Humiliation**

### Dalio's Reflection on Predictability

- Story of Britain's rise obvious in retrospect, but another thing to position oneself well by anticipating and seeing it happen at the time
- Wonders what he would have thought looking at indicators/systems at the time
- Important to have data and decision rules to see what would have actually done and results
- Can now see what indicators would have shown at the time — would have painted picture just described
- Picture would **not** have been crystal clear that British Empire would become dominant
- In early 1700s looking at indicators: would have seen **Dutch still at peak**, **Bourbon France as major power on the rise**, **bullish conditions for both**

### Why Not the French?

#### France's Intellectual and Economic Strengths

- Early 1700s: France center of education and learning, hub of Enlightenment
- Famous thinkers: **Voltaire, Montesquieu**
- Home to booming publishing industry
- 1720–1780: number of books on arts and science published in Paris doubled
- Literacy rates in France close to doubled over 18th century

#### The Debt Bubble and John Law's Experiment

- France would have shown up economically strong in early stage of big debt cycle upswing
- Just before investment boom about to turn into bubble, then bust
- France's most famous economist: **John Law** (Scotsman) — thought creating new money would stimulate economy
- 1716: created national bank with ability to issue paper money backed by land, gold, silver, state bills
- Began upswing in cycle
- Original capital for **Banque Générale** provided by shareholders (also sat on bank's board)
- France had stock market since 1673 (**Finance Minister Jean-Baptiste Colbert's Ordinance of Trade**)
- Law created **Company of the West** (Mississippi Company) — trading company with monopoly rights in French Louisiana
- Law allowed French government debt to purchase Mississippi Company shares
- New company with exciting frontier story + bank and government finances supporting endeavor = all right ingredients
- Company expanded, state debt holders jumped at ability to convert debt into equity
- Created what was perceived to be great investment
- Stock soared, eventually becoming bubble
- When burst, both shares and bills rapidly lost value — classic reason: outstanding claims on real assets much greater than real assets backing claims

#### Flight to Hard Currency and Financial Collapse

- **People in France fled from depreciating paper money toward hard currency coinage**
- New laws prohibited charging interest rates above 5% — only most credit-worthy borrowers and stable investments could receive capital
- Became nearly impossible for new businesses to receive funding
- Wasn't enough real money

#### Costly Wars Drain French Finances

Major wars France was involved in:

- **War of the League of Augsburg (1688–97)**: France under Louis XIV expanded into western Germany, spurring war against England, Spain, Austria, German states
- **War of the Spanish Succession (1701–14)**: France allied with Spain fought alliance of England, Austria, Netherlands to contest Spanish throne inheritance. French heir took throne, but with concessions (giving up Spanish territory in Italy and Belgium to Austria; France giving England and Netherlands colonial and trade concessions)
- **War of the Austrian Succession (1740–48)**: France allied with Spain, Prussia, other German principalities fought Austria and UK over German princes' territorial ambitions
- **Seven Years' War (1756–63)**: France allied with Austria, Sweden, Russia fought Britain and Prussia over German territories and French and British colonies abroad (particularly North America) — also known as French and Indian War
- **American Revolution (1775–83)**: France and Spain allied with American revolutionary forces against British government

- While wars produced territorial and strategic gains, **cost much more than they brought in**, eventually severely damaged French government's finances
- Without modern financial system, France had more difficulty funding government through debt than Britain — had to rely more on burdensome taxes (unpopular)

#### Inequality and Ineffective Governance

- **Along with extreme income inequality, there was corruption and extravagance at the top**
- Court of **King Louis XVI** infamous for frivolous spending — **Marie Antoinette's Hamlet**, ornamental farm near Versailles built at great expense to replicate rustic village
- **Two major wars — Seven Years' War and American Revolution — led to massive deficits**
- American Revolution deficits: around 2–3% of GDP, about third of France's annual tax revenue
- American Revolution popularized Enlightenment ideas of liberty and equality
- **Bad harvests in 1788 and 1789 led to soaring bread prices and famines** — recipe for revolution
- **France's inefficient and unrepresentative political decision-making system meant government unable to raise needed revenues or enact needed changes**
- Decisions from ancien régime could be and often were undermined at virtually every lower level
- Nobility and clergy resisted decisions hurting them, carved out broad privileges
- Local authorities (**parlements**) needed to enact tax policy but often resisted
- Closest thing to legislative body: **Estates General** (representatives of three estates: clergy, nobility, commoners)
- Consent necessary to levy new national taxes
- Powers and procedures unclear — how representatives chosen, how many votes each estate got unsettled
- 1789: Third Estate (commoners, 98% of population) formed own assembly, invited First and Second Estates to join
- King closed their meeting hall to stop National Assembly from meeting

#### Revolution, Terror, and Hyperinflation

- Protests, riots, insurrection arose
- **1791: newly elected National Convention declared France a republic**
- January 1793: **Louis XVI** (by then "Citizen Louis") sentenced to death
- Classic in revolutions: violence began soon after, those deemed insufficiently zealous purged
- Estimated 20,000–30,000 people executed during **French Reign of Terror**
- By 1795: France broke, **assignat** (currency printed to finance government spending) experiencing hyperinflation
- Revolution led to counterreaction — revolution's leaders arrested, new constitution written and approved
- New system (Directorate) proved ineffective, immediately crippled by financial problems
- **Government continued to print money and forced wealthy citizens to loan it funds**
- Inflationary spiral halted by introduction of hard currency acquired through **Napoleon's successful military conquests** in Italy and decision to declare bankruptcy on two-thirds of government's debt
- Additional measures (increased taxes) further strengthened government's fiscal condition
- 1796: government held ceremony destroying presses used to print money

### Enter Napoleon

- Bubble, big wealth gaps, costly wars led to bust then revolution
- Threw out old order, put in new one with revolutionary leaders fighting with each other
- Produced 10 years of painful chaos requiring strong leader to get control of mess
- Consistent with classic melodramatic script played innumerable times in past
- **As if on cue, Napoleon entered the picture**
- **Napoleon was classic hero rising to the occasion** — gained sterling reputation as military commander as France attempted to spread republican system across Europe
- Very popular
- 1799: led coup to install himself as first consul and eventually emperor, held dictatorial powers until 1814
- **Armed with centralized power and widespread support, he stabilized the economy and professionalized the government**
- France widely seen as empire on the rise, formidable rival to other European powers

#### Napoleon's Military Campaigns

- When Austria and Russia declared war on France, Napoleon scored sizable early military victories
- Before long: controlled Spain, Portugal, Italy, much of Germany
- Won't go through history of Napoleonic Wars except to say: like other such leaders, he overreached
- Napoleon's invasion of Russia swung tide of war against him
- **In the end, France was defeated. Great Britain and Russia were the primary victors**
- Significant factor: **UK's much greater financial strength allowed UK to lend a lot of money to European coalition forces against France**
- Both financial resources and naval power allowed Britain to stay in fight even as it and allies suffered repeated defeats

### A New World Order: The Congress of Vienna

- After war, victors come together and create new world order
- Happened at **Congress of Vienna**
- Just as victors of Thirty Years' War had done at Westphalia, **quadruple alliance of Great Britain, Austria, Prussia, and Russia reorganized world order in their favor at Congress of Vienna (1814–15)**
- **Created system of checks and balances among European powers that would more or less hold for next century**
- Geopolitical importance well-described by **Henry Kissinger**:

> It may not have fulfilled all the hopes of an idealistic generation, but it gave this generation something perhaps more precious: a period of stability which permitted their hopes to be realized without a major war or a permanent revolution… The period of stability which ensued was the best proof that a "legitimate" order had been constructed, an order accepted by all the major powers, so that henceforth they sought adjustment within its framework rather than in its overthrow.

- All major powers represented in Vienna, though most important decisions negotiated by core group and France itself
- Like US at Paris Peace Conference after WWI and negotiations after WWII, **UK didn't seek to gain significant new territories**
- **Primary goal: address power imbalances in Europe that had led to wars**
- **Areas that had previously consisted of weak and divided states (Italy, Germany, Low Countries) saw significant territorial consolidation to counterbalance more centralized states like France**
- Agreements on navigation of international rivers supported expansion of trade
- Treaties of Paris aimed to contain but not destroy France (suffered only minimal loss of territory)
- **Victorious powers all monarchies, many polices aimed at restoring old status quo** (e.g., returning Bourbon dynasty to power in France)
- Even so, new ideas of Enlightenment continued to have influence
- **Governments shifted to more representative and rule-of-law-based systems, though to varying degrees (Tsarist Russia remained largely autocratic)**
- England: liberalization came about through gradual reforms
- On continent: series of revolutions (most famously liberal Revolutions of 1848) spurred changes
- **In time, nationalist movements led to unification of Germany and Italy, as well as destabilization of multiethnic Austrian and Ottoman empires**

### British Power Approaches Its Peak

- No power benefited more from new stability than British Empire
- **Not only were Britain's main economic and military rivals weakened, but power equilibrium allowed UK to avoid expensive military conflicts close to home and focus on trade and colonies** — policy known as **"splendid isolation,"** set stage for **"Imperial Century"**
- Some bad economic periods (e.g., Panic of 1825 in UK, panics of 1837 and 1873 in US)
- Military conflicts (e.g., Crimean War between Russia on one side and Ottoman Empire + coalition of Western European powers on other)
- But not significant enough to change big picture: very prosperous period with British on top
- At peak in late 19th century around 1870: British produced 20% of world's income, controlled 40% of global exports, 20% of world's land mass, 25% of world's population
- Pound became world's undisputed reserve currency
- Charts on following pages paint picture of Britain's dominant strength

#### Geopolitical Expansion

- UK continued to expand abroad throughout 19th century, eventually encompassing Canada, Australia, India, large portions of Africa
- Even where British Empire didn't explicitly take control, increasingly able to intervene abroad to gain trade access on uneven terms (e.g., **Opium Wars** against China ending with treaty ensuring UK's ability to export opium to China despite local Chinese laws against it)
- Maintaining colonies gave UK assured source of commodities, wealth, income, preferential trade arrangements

### The Top

#### Reserve Currency Status and Global Financial Dominance

- Pound's status as reserve currency complemented dominance in colonial expansion, military reach, global trade, investment flows
- **UK's share of global exports rose with Industrial Revolution and spread of empire, peaking around 1850 at about 40% of global exports**
- Share of trade denominated in sterling greater than UK's trade share alone
- 1850–1914: around 60% of global trade denominated in pounds
- Set of conditions sowed seeds of decline that typify top phase of Big Cycle

#### Current Account Dynamics

- Even as UK's share of world exports declined, UK ran persistent current account surplus throughout period
- After 1870: comprised of persistent trade deficit funded by returns on overseas investments
- Income from current account surpluses funded increasing share of global cross-border investment as other countries became more attractive to invest in

#### Sterling's Global Role

- 1818: **English Rothschild bank** made first major government loan (to Prussia)
- As pound became increasingly liquid, wave of other sovereign borrowers followed
- Global debt, global trade, global capital flows increasingly denominated in sterling
- Trust in pound bolstered by economic management of **Bank of England**, which increasingly operated as **"lender of last resort"** to mitigate effects of banking panics

### Seeds of Decline

- **Even as British Empire continued to expand territorial and financial reach over final decades of 19th century, seeds of fall were evident**
- Driven by classic factors of:
  1. **Declining competitiveness**
  2. **Rising inequality and conflict**
  3. **Rise of new rivals, particularly Germany and US**

### Declining Competitiveness

#### The Second Industrial Revolution

- Broader story of economic growth in mid-to-late 1800s: **Second Industrial Revolution**
- Sustained period of innovation where science and engineering played major role
- Synthetics and new alloys produced, use of new energy sources (petroleum, electricity) exploded
- When telephone and incandescent light bulb developed, automobiles soon followed
- **Transportation, communications, and infrastructure improved**
- Rise of corporate capitalism enhanced productivity
- **Result: sizable increase in output per worker in countries able to make switch efficiently — primarily US and Germany**
- UK didn't keep up, even though British inventions key to many new developments
- UK's failure to reorganize industries led to marked declines in output per worker relative to other leading industrial powers
- Can see secular shift in innovation and economic power in charts

### Rising Inequality

- Gains from industrialization distributed very unevenly in UK
- Produced extreme levels of inequality
- By late 1800s: **top 1% of population owned over 70% of all wealth**, more than in peer countries
- **Top 10% owned astounding 93% of wealth**
- Peak in wealth gap coincided with peak in British Empire around 1900
- Beginning of next wave of conflict over wealth and power due to large wealth gaps and classic late Big Cycle conditions

#### Social and Labor Reforms

- Combination of social change and rising inequality sparked significant tensions
- England's policy response in mid-1800s: reform bills expanding voting rights, reducing corrupt practices making elections less democratic
- By early 1900s: political reforms followed by social reforms
- Included: public pension system, medical and unemployment insurance, provision of free lunches for school children
- Organized labor also on the rise, strengthening workers' bargaining power
- By 1911: around 25% of eligible men were union members
- **Labour Party** became significant force in politics
- Greater power took form of increasingly large strikes — e.g., first national strike by coal miners in 1912, led to minimum wage for miners

### Geopolitical Rivals Emerge

- **In addition to domestic issues, UK faced challengers to empire abroad**
- Competing for influence: France in Africa, Russia in Middle East and Central Asia, US in Americas
- **Most significant rivalry: with Germany**
- United States (other great rising power) remained blissfully isolationist with big ocean allowing it to largely ignore conflicts in Europe

#### Germany's Rise Through Education and Innovation

- **When new world order began at Congress of Vienna, Germany still divided into number of smaller states**
- While Austrian Empire (ruled by Habsburgs) had influence, Prussia swiftly rising with one of strongest armies in Europe
- **Over next century, successfully unified other German states, becoming first-rate power**
- **Achieved thanks in large part to Otto von Bismarck's brilliant strategic and diplomatic leadership and other classic ingredients for success: strong education and competitiveness**
- **Once unified, Germany experienced classic virtuous cycle of power on the rise**
- **Viewing effective education system as crucial step in quest to raise economy to level of Great Britain's, new Germany — and predecessor states — built one from ground up**
- Focused on teaching both practical trade skills and high-level scientific knowledge (theoretical and applied)
- Starting 1860s: primary education mandatory for all, enforced by law
- Germany established three new research universities
- **German government provided credit to corporations, along with technical advice and assistance; awarded grants to inventors and immigrant entrepreneurs; bestowed gifts of machinery; allowed rebates and exemptions of duties on imports of industrial equipment**
- **Germany maintained strong rule of law, explicitly aimed at economic development**

<!-- pp. 301-320 -->

## Chapter 10: The Big Cycle Rise and Decline of the British Empire and the Pound (continued)

### Germany's Rise and Wilhelm II's Shift to World Power

- Germany's manufacturing output surged from 5% to 13% of world share between 1860-1900
- **By 1900, Germany's GDP surpassed Britain's** (excluding empire), though Britain remained leading trading nation
- Germany dominated Nobel Prizes (1900-1913) and patent applications, signaling innovation leadership
- **Otto von Bismarck** prioritized economic development and diplomacy with international competitors
- **Wilhelm II became emperor in 1888**, forced Bismarck to resign, adopted policy of turning Germany into a world power
- Wilhelm built up Germany's military, especially navy, **setting off an arms race with the UK**
- Multiple rivalries built across Europe: UK-Germany, France-Germany, concerns about Russian industrialization, Austria-Russia struggling for Balkans influence
- Countries intertwined through marriage and commerce more than ever, most believed war wouldn't happen
- **1914: the powder keg exploded into all-out war** — first world war because world had become so small and interconnected

### World War I: The First Global Conflict

- War was terrible: **8.5 million soldiers and 13 million civilians killed**, all of Europe exhausted, weakened, and indebted
- Russia devolved into revolution (1917); Spanish flu arrived (1918), killing 20-50 million globally
- More people died as percentage of European population than in Napoleonic Wars or Thirty Years' War
- War ended and next new world order was created

### The Paris Peace Conference and Treaty of Versailles (1919)

- **Victors — US, Britain, France, Japan, and Italy — met at Paris Peace Conference** to lay out new world order
- US now recognized as leading power, played big role in negotiations
- Term **"new world order"** coined to describe **Woodrow Wilson's vision** for global governance (League of Nations, though this quickly failed)
- Congress of Vienna (1815) created sustainable order; **Paris Peace Conference did the opposite** — made second war inevitable though not apparent at time
- Losing powers (Germany, Austria-Hungary, Ottoman Empire, Bulgaria) had territories carved up, **forced to pay reparations to victors**
- **Debt burdens contributed to inflationary depression in Germany from 1920 to 1923**
- Elsewhere, world entered **decade of peace and prosperity, the Roaring '20s**
- **Debts and wealth gaps built up burst in 1929, causing the Great Depression**
- Two big boom/bust cycles came unusually close together, though followed classic stages

### The Great Depression and Rise of Populism

- Great Depression coupled with large wealth gaps led to **rise in populism and extremism in nearly every major country**
- **In some countries (US, UK)**: big redistributions of wealth and political power while capitalism and democracy maintained
- **In others with weaker economies (Germany, Japan, Italy, Spain)**: populist dictators seized control and sought to expand empires
- **Classically, before all-out wars begin, there is typically about a decade of economic, technological, geopolitical, and capital skirmishing**
- Time between depression and WWII consistent with this rule
- Germany and Japan became more expansionist, competed with UK, US, France for resources and territorial influence
- Tensions boiled over into war

### World War II: Even More Costly

- **WWII, just two decades after WWI, was even more costly in lives and money**
- **Germany and Japan lost; US, UK, and Soviet Union won, though economically UK and Soviet Union lost too and US gained enormously in relative wealth**
- GDP per capita in Germany and Japan fell by at least half
- Currencies collapsed in aftermath of war
- **Winners of war got together and determined new world order in 1945**

## Chapter 10: The Decline (British Empire and Pound)

### Allied Victory 1945: US Emerges as Dominant Empire

- **Allied victory in 1945 produced tremendous shift of wealth and power, with US emerging as world's dominant empire just as British had after Napoleonic Wars**
- British left with: large debts, expensive empire, more competitive rivals, population with big wealth gaps leading to political gaps
- **Took another 20 years for British pound to fully lose its status as international reserve currency**
- Just as English language deeply woven into international business, same true of reserve currencies — other central banks continued holding sizable reserves in pounds through 1950s
- **One-third of international trade still denominated in sterling in 1960**
- **Pound had been losing status since end of war** because smart investors recognized contrast between UK's and US's financial conditions, UK's increased debt load, and UK's low net reserves

### The Pound's Suspended Convertibility (1947) and Devaluation (1949)

- **Decline in British pound was protracted affair involving several significant devaluations**
- After failed attempt to make pound convertible in 1946-47, **devalued by 30% against dollar in 1949**
- Over next two decades, Britain's declining competitiveness led to repeated balance of payments strains, culminating with **devaluation of 1967**
- Around this time, **deutschemark took pound's place as world's second most widely held reserve currency**

#### 1940s Crisis Years for the Pound

- War required UK to borrow immensely from allies and colonies; obligations held in sterling
- When war ended, UK could not meet debt obligations without raising taxes or cutting government spending
- UK mandated that debt assets (bonds) could not be proactively sold by former colonies
- US anxious for UK to restore convertibility ASAP — restrictions reduced liquidity in global economy, affecting US export profits
- Bank of England eager to remove capital controls to restore pound's role as global trading currency, increase financial sector revenues in London, encourage international investors to continue saving in sterling
- **1946: agreement reached in which US would provide UK with loan of $3.75 billion (about 10% of UK GDP)** to offer buffer against potential run on pound
- When partial convertibility introduced July 1947, pound came under considerable selling pressure
- UK and Sterling Area countries turned to austerity to maintain pound's peg to dollar
- Restrictions imposed on luxury goods imports, defense expenditures slashed, dollar and gold reserves drawn down
- Agreements made among sterling economies to not diversify reserve holdings to dollar
- **Prime Minister Clement Attlee** gave dramatic speech calling for spirit of wartime sacrifice

> We are engaged in another battle for Britain. This battle cannot be won by the few. It demands a united effort by the whole nation. I am confident that this united effort will be forthcoming and that we shall again conquer.

- Immediately following speech, run on pound accelerated
- **By end of August, convertibility was suspended, much to anger of US and other international investors** who had bought sterling assets in lead-up to convertibility
- Governor of National Bank of Belgium threatened to stop transacting in sterling, requiring diplomatic intervention
- **Devaluation came two years later, as policymakers in both UK and US realized pound couldn't return to convertibility at current rate**
- Competitiveness returned, current account improved, by mid-to-late 1950s full convertibility restored

### Failed International Efforts to Support Pound (1950s-1960s) and 1967 Devaluation

- Though 1949 devaluation helped short term, pound faced recurring balance of payments strains
- Very concerning to international policymakers, who feared collapse in value of sterling or rapid shift to dollar could prove detrimental to Bretton Woods monetary system (particularly given backdrop of Cold War and concerns around communism)
- **As result, numerous efforts made to shore up pound and preserve its role as source of international liquidity**
- UK mandated all trade within Common Market denominated in pounds, all currencies pegged to sterling
- Result: for 1950s and early 1960s, UK best understood as regional economic power and sterling as regional reserve currency
- **Yet measures didn't fix problem: UK too indebted and too uncompetitive; couldn't pay debts and still buy what needed to import**
- **Sterling had to be devalued again in 1967**
- **After that, even Sterling Area countries were unwilling to hold their reserves in pounds unless UK guaranteed their underlying value in dollars**

#### The 1960s Balance of Payments Crisis

- UK's current account deteriorated, gold reserves fell over decade, accelerating in 1967
- Sharp rate hikes amid currency stabilization efforts
- Central banks began selling sterling reserves and buying dollars, deutschemarks, yen, as opposed to simply accumulating fewer pounds in new reserve holdings
- Average share of sterling in central bank reserve holdings collapsed within two years
- **Countries that continued to hold high share of reserves in pounds after 1968 were holding de facto dollars because Sterling Agreement of 1968 guaranteed 90% of their dollar value**

### Europe After World War II

- Terrible costs of war push countries to create new world orders in their aftermaths to ensure such wars never happen again
- Naturally, new world orders revolve around victor, often the newly ascendant empire
- After WWII, that was clearly the US

#### Most Important Geopolitical Elements of Post-War Order

- **US was dominant power, which made it de facto global police force**
- Tensions arose between US and world's second leading power, **Soviet Union**
- US and allies formed military alliance **NATO**; Soviet states formed **Warsaw Pact**; two faced off in **Cold War**

- **United Nations established to resolve global disputes**
- Classically, headquartered in heart of ascendant empire (New York), with main power organ **Security Council** dominated by war's victors

#### Most Important Financial Elements of New World Order

- **Bretton Woods monetary system, which established dollar as world's reserve currency**
- **IMF and World Bank**, designed to support new global financial system
- **New York as new global financial center**

#### European Perspective: Shift from Balance of Power to US/Soviet Overshadowing

- From European perspective, **key aspect of new world order was shift from balance of power in which preeminent European powers were on top to world in which they were exhausted and overshadowed by new superpowers** that dwarfed any one European state (especially as colonies gained independence)
- Given these pressures and clear lesson of costs of division that World Wars taught, **value of European unity was clear**
- That was impetus for new European order that gradually developed into **European Union**

### The Formation of the European Union

- Story of **Robert Schuman**, key EU founder, helps explain why Europe came together
- Schuman's father was French citizen who became German citizen when home region of **Alsace-Lorraine** annexed by Germans in 1871
- Schuman born German citizen, but became French citizen when Alsace-Lorraine returned to France after WWI
- As politician in WWII, he joined **Vichy government** before abandoning it for **French Resistance**
- Ended war in hiding, with 100,000 Reichsmark bounty on his head
- Key partner to Schuman was **West Germany's first post-war chancellor, Konrad Adenauer**
- Centrist mayor, driven from political life by Nazis, sent to concentration camp in 1944
- Following election as chancellor as **Christian Democrat** in 1949, policies focused on rebuilding German economy, reconciling with other European powers, opposing communism
- Schuman and Adenauer's project, along with rest of EU's founders, was to **make war "not merely unthinkable, but materially impossible"**

#### The European Coal and Steel Community

- First step: create **European Coal and Steel Community**
- Sounds like narrow economic pact, but explicit goal was to create European federation
- From **Schuman Declaration**:

> The pooling of coal and steel production should immediately provide for the setting up of common foundations for economic development as a first step in the federation of Europe, and will change the destinies of those regions which have long been devoted to the manufacture of munitions of war, of which they have been the most constant victims.

- Agreement created supranational bodies — **High Authority, Common Assembly, Court of Justice** — that bound individual countries to its decisions and regulations
- Had ability to levy taxes, could issue loans, set up programs for worker welfare
- Six nations signed on, more joined over time
- Eventually evolved into customs union (1957, via **Treaty of Rome**), opened up countries' borders (1985, via **Schengen Agreement**), and eventually agreed on framework for political and economic union, including shared European citizenship (1992, via **Maastricht Treaty**)

#### The Euro and Economic Integration

- As is classic, new European geopolitical order came with new financial/economic order
- **Maastricht Treaty** created basis for new common currency (**euro**) and common economic rules, including rules around government deficits
- Integration of 27 member states (and 400+ million people), many of whom had been at war with one another in past, is impressive feat — **puts EU on similar standing to other great powers**

#### EU's Current Challenges and Decline

- European Union's relative declines and crises in early 21st century occurred for classic reasons Big Cycle declines occurred, reflected in eight measures of power described in Chapter 2
- Same reasons other empires experienced crises
- More specifically: **Europe's debt is large, economy fundamentally weak, internal conflicts relatively large, vitality and inventiveness relatively weak, military not strong**
- Wealth and income inequalities between and within member countries fueled rise of populists, many oppose European Union, succeeded in causing UK to leave it
- In short, from position of leading empire not long ago, **Europe as whole (and UK with it) has slipped to position of secondary power**

## Chapter 11: The Big Cycle Rise and Decline of the United States and the Dollar

### Introduction to US Big Cycle

- This chapter covers **Big Cycle rise of US beginning in 19th century, its gradual surpassing of UK as world's most powerful empire, and its recent decline**
- As story of US as world's leading empire still unfolding and highly relevant to world today, **will be going through its Big Cycle in more detail than for Dutch and British**
- Especially as relates to **dollar's status as global reserve currency** and economic and monetary policy forces that have impacted it

### US Power Index Over Time

- Chart shows eight types of power that make up overall US arc
- **In them you can see story behind US's rise and decline since 1700**
- Strong development and excellence in education led to advances in innovation and technology, competitiveness in world markets, economic output
- All fueled development of financial markets and US as financial center, leadership in military strength and world trade
- With significant lag, emergence of dollar as reserve currency
- Relative advantages in education, competitiveness, and trade have fallen
- Those in innovation and technology, reserve currency status, and financial markets and financial center status remain strong
- **What this chart doesn't show are deviations in US income and balance sheet conditions and its internal conflicts, both of which are more concerning**

### The Six Stages of US Internal Order Cycle

- Chart combines all factors to show overall arc of US from before Revolutionary War
- Numbers mark approximate times of six stages of internal order cycle:
  1. New Order
  2. Civil War and Industrial Revolution
  3. New Order 1865
  4. WWI, WWII
  5. New Order 1945, Declining Dollar, Revolution
  6. Rising Inequality & High Internal Conflict

### THE RISE

#### The US Revolution and Post-Revolution Process

- **US went through usual revolution and post-revolution process** in which it created new domestic order as:
  1. Coordinated group of strong leaders fought to gain control
  2. That group won and consolidated control
  3. New leadership had vision supported by population
  4. But it split into factions with conflicts over how government should work to implement that vision
  5. Eventually, these factions figured out system for control and laid it out in agreements (at first in **Articles of Confederation**, then in **Constitution**)
  6. Set up parts of government (legal and credit system, legal system, legislative systems, military, etc.)
  7. Put people in jobs and made it work well

- US did these things in uniquely peaceful way through negotiations, near-total respect for agreements, and good designs for governance that gave it great start

#### Education, Innovation, and Economic Development

- In chart showing eight types of power: rapidly improving levels of education preceded big rises in innovation, technology, and competitiveness
- Lasted until World Wars, with interruption during US Civil War
- Many ups and downs in both domestic and external money/debt, economic, and military circumstances
- All followed archetypical patterns driven by same basic cause/effect relationships
- While ascent of US most pronounced after WWII, **it really started in late 1800s**

#### The Second Industrial Revolution and Progressive Era

- **After US Civil War came Second Industrial Revolution**, one of those **classic times in which peaceful pursuit of wealth and prosperity created great gains in incomes, technologies, and wealth in England, continental Europe, and United States**
- **In US, these gains were financed through system of free-market capitalism that, as is classic, produced both lots of wealth and big wealth gaps**
- Gaps led to discontent and Progressive Era policies that broke up rich and powerful monopolies ("trust busting"), raised taxes on rich
- Started with passage of constitutional amendment to allow federal income taxes in 1913
- US's increased strengths reflected in rising shares of global economic output and world trade, as well as growing financial strength (exemplified by **New York becoming world's leading financial center**)
- Continuing leadership in innovation, great usage of its financial products

### The Long Ascent of the Dollar and US Capital Markets

#### Early US Banking: Fragmented and Crisis-Prone

- Dollar's path to being world's dominant reserve currency was far from straightforward
- In US's first century of existence, financial system completely underdeveloped
- Banking worked in United States in classic ways described in Chapters 3 and 4
- Hard money put into banks that together lent out much more than they had
- That Ponzi scheme unraveled, so banks failed to meet commitments and devalued money
- **US had no central bank to control financial markets or act as lender of last resort**
- **US went through many boom/bust cycles, in which classically a flurry of debt-financed investments (into land, railroads, etc.) became overextended, leading to credit losses and credit crunch**
- **As result, banking system panics were extremely common**
- In New York alone, eight significant banking panics occurred between 1836 and 1913
- Regional banking panics also common
- This because highly fragmented banking system had rigid amount of currency, no deposit insurance, and pyramidal reserve system (small number of large banks in New York serving as "correspondents" or holding reserves for high percentage of nation's banks) that heightened risk of contagion from one bank going under

#### New York as Trading Center, Not Yet Financial Center

- **Like London, New York was well-established as trading center long before it became global financial center, development that didn't occur until after turn of 20th century**
- Only two US banks made list of top 20 largest global banks in 1913, at numbers 13 and 17
- In comparison, British banks occupied nine slots, including three of top five
- For perspective, at this point US was far larger than UK in economic output, and they were neck and neck in export market share

<!-- pp. 321-340 -->

## The Second Industrial Revolution and the Gilded Age (Late 1800s)

### The Rise of New York as a Financial Center

- Financial innovations emerged from NYC's needs as a major trading center
- **Investment banking** took off in the 1800s as a clearinghouse for capital flowing from Europe to finance the US boom
- Insurance companies developed more rapidly than banks in the pre-WWI period—large insurance trusts were bigger than large banks
- US stock market reflected the economy's dynamism and rapid change compared to European markets
- **Second half of 19th century**: boom period of peace and prosperity, called the **"Second Industrial Revolution," "Gilded Age," and "Robber Barron Era"**
- Period where capitalism and innovation flourished, but wealth gaps widened enormously, decadence was apparent, and resentment built
- Backlash started around 1900; classic debt bust in 1907 led to creation of **Federal Reserve** in 1913
- By 1910, US stock market capitalization surpassed Great Britain
- New sectors rose quickly: **US Steel** founded 1901, became most valuable US company 15 years later

### World War I (1914-1918)

- War few expected and nobody expected to last so long
- **US was not in WWI for most of it**—only major country to maintain convertibility to gold during the war
- European economies and markets badly hurt; European government policies further undermined faith in currencies
- US relative financial and economic position benefited from the war
- Allied wartime debts were largely owed to the US, boosting use of dollar for global government debt

### Paris Peace Conference (1919)

> "Following the standard script, the winning powers—in this case the US, Britain, France, Japan, and Italy—met after the war to set out the new world order."

- **Paris Peace Conference** took place early 1919, lasted six months, led to **Treaty of Versailles**
- Territories of losing powers (Germany, Austria-Hungary, Ottoman Empire, Bulgaria) carved up and put under control of winning empires
- Losing powers put into deep debt to winning powers to repay war costs—debts payable in gold
- Chart shows devaluation of GBR, FRA, DEU currencies against dollar during WWI

### Post-WWI Geopolitical Landscape

- US benefited geopolitically—played key role in shaping new world order, though remained more isolationist
- Britain continued to expand and oversee global colonial empire
- Monetary system in immediate post-war period was in flux
- Most countries endeavored to restore gold convertibility; currency stability against gold came only after sharp devaluations and inflation

### The Roaring '20s

- Period of peace and prosperity fueled by great innovations and productivity
- Capital markets boom produced big debts and big wealth gaps late in upswing
- **Lot of debt created in the '20s** (promises to deliver paper money convertible to gold) to buy speculative assets, particularly stocks
- **Federal Reserve tightened monetary policy in 1929**, which caused bubble to burst and global Great Depression to begin
- Brought economic suffering to virtually all nations
- Led to fighting over wealth within and between countries
- Led to hot wars that began a decade later

## THE TOP: Post-WWII World Order

### WWII's Impact on US Relative Power

- Allied victory in 1945 produced next shift in world order—tremendous shift of wealth and power
- **US came out the big winner** because:
  - US sold and lent a lot before and during the war
  - Basically all fighting took place off US territory, so US wasn't physically damaged
  - US deaths were comparatively low relative to other major countries

### The Post-War Geopolitical and Military System

- Victorious powers met to determine new world order and new money/credit systems
- **US, Russia (USSR), and Great Britain** emerged as world's great powers—US clearly richest and most powerful militarily
- Germany, Japan, Italy largely destroyed; Great Britain essentially bankrupt; France devastated by war, contributed little to victory
- China in civil war, resumed right after Japan's surrender
- **Good cooperation between US and Russia immediately after war, but didn't take long for the two greatest powers with opposing ideologies to enter a "cold" war**
- Chart shows aggregate power indices for US, UK, Russia, China since end of WWII
- Russia rose relative to US until 1980 but never nearly as powerful
- After 1980, Russia began decline while China began rapid ascent; US continued gradual decline

### The Truman Doctrine (March 1947)

> "Every nation must choose between alternative ways of life. The choice is too often not a free one. One way of life is based upon the will of the majority, and is distinguished by free institutions, representative government, free elections, guarantees of individual liberty, freedom of speech and religion, and freedom from political oppression. The second way of life is based upon the will of a minority forcibly imposed upon the majority. It relies upon terror and oppression, a controlled press and radio, fixed elections, and the suppression of personal freedoms."

### International Relations vs. Domestic Governance

- **International relations driven much more by raw power dynamics** than domestic governance
- Between countries, raw power matters most; laws, rules, even mutually agreed-upon treaties and organizations for arbitration (League of Nations, United Nations, World Trade Organization) don't matter much
- **This makes having a strong military and strong military alliances so important**
- 1949: 12 countries in US camp formed **NATO** military alliance (more joined later)
- 1954: **SEATO** established among US, UK, Australia, France, New Zealand, Philippines, Thailand, Pakistan
- Eight countries in Soviet camp formed **Warsaw Pact** in 1955

### Nuclear Weapons and Military Power

- **Americans and Soviets invested massively in building up their nuclear weapons**—number of other countries followed
- Today, 11 countries have nuclear weapons or are on brink of having them, in varying amounts and degrees of capability
- Nuclear weapons give big negotiating chip in world power game
- While no nuclear wars, US fought number of conventional wars since WWII: **Korean War** (1950s), **Vietnam War** (1960s-70s), two **Gulf Wars** (1990, 2003), **War in Afghanistan** (2001-2021)
- These costly in terms of money, lives, and public support for United States
- For **Soviet Union**, spending enough to compete with US militarily and maintain empire pushed it into bankruptcy

### Current Military Assessment

- **US remains strongest military power overall**, but not dominant in all parts of world in all ways
- Military challenges to US are rising
- Significant chance US would lose wars against China and Russia in their geographic areas of strength—or at least be unacceptably harmed
- Could also be unacceptably harmed by some second-tier powers
- Most worrying high-risk scenario: **forceful move by China to bring Taiwan under its control**

### Future Military Conflicts and Technology

- Next high-stakes military conflict will be very different from previous ones due to new technologies
- Classically, country that wins wars spends more, invests more, and outlasts the opposition—delicate balance
- **Biggest military risk for leading powers: they lose the economic and technology wars** because military spending takes government money away from social programs, and military technologies go hand in hand with private sector technologies

### International Currency Dynamics

- In dealings between countries, transactions more at arm's length
- Less easy to make currency artificially cheap, harming holders
- Internationally traded currencies more likely to be better value currencies
- Relevant when currencies are storehold of wealth in form of debt denominated in them
- Sometimes too much debt around the world; in all governments' interests to devalue currencies
- At such times, gold (and recently digital currencies) can be preferable
- Governments more likely to outlaw alternative currencies, though can't fully outlaw them
- When money and credit systems based on fiat currencies break down, eventually leads to hard money monetary systems

### The Post-War Monetary and Economic Systems

- **One system for US-led camp, one for Soviet-led camp**—also nonaligned countries with own currencies not widely accepted
- Representatives of 44 countries gathered at **Bretton Woods, New Hampshire** in 1944 to make monetary system linking dollar to gold and other currencies to dollar
- Soviet Union's system built around ruble, which nobody wanted
- **Transactions between countries very different from transactions within countries**—governments want to control money used within borders
- By increasing/decreasing supply, cost of borrowing, and value, government has enormous power

### How the Bretton Woods System Worked

- In post-war monetary system, within countries, people and companies used government-controlled paper money
- **When buying from another country, typically exchanged own country's paper currency for other country's paper currency with help of central bank that settled with other country's central bank in gold**
- If American, paid in dollars; seller from another country either exchanged at central bank for local currency or held believing better storehold of wealth than own money
- Gold left US central bank's reserve account and went into other country's central bank accounts; dollars accumulated abroad

### Dollar as World's Leading Reserve Currency

- **Dollar became world's leading reserve currency**—natural because **two World Wars made US richest and most powerful country by far**
- By end of WWII, US had amassed greatest gold/money savings ever—about two-thirds of all government-held gold/money in world, equivalent to eight years of import purchases
- Even after war, continued to earn a lot of money by exporting

### Marshall and Dodge Plans

- **Economies of Europe and Japan destroyed by war**
- **US supplied them with massive aid packages (Marshall and Dodge plans)** which were:
  - a) Good for devastated nations
  - b) Good for US economically because countries used money to buy US goods
  - c) Good for US's geopolitical influence
  - d) Good for reinforcing dollar's position as world's dominant reserve currency

### Post-War US Monetary Policy (1933-1951)

- Federal Reserve controlled amount of money, cost of money (interest rates), and where money went to serve greater objectives rather than free market
- Fed printed a lot of money to buy debt, capped interest rates lenders could charge
- Controlled what money was allowed to go into
- High inflation did not drive interest rates to unacceptable heights; government regulations prevented other investment options from becoming more attractive than government debt

### Post-War Economic Boom

- **Following brief post-war recession due to decline of military spending, US entered prolonged period of peace and prosperity as is typical when new Big Cycle begins**
- Post-war recession saw unemployment double (to around 4%), ~20 million people needed employment outside military
- Removal of rationing laws fueled consumer spending surge
- Cheap mortgages available for veterans, leading to housing boom
- Return to profit-making raised demand for labor; employment rebounded quickly
- Exports strong because Marshall/Dodge plans fueled foreign appetite for US goods
- US private sector went global, invested abroad from 1945 through 1970s
- Stocks cheap, dividend yields high—result was multidecade bull market that reinforced NYC's dominance as world's financial center
- Further strengthened dollar as reserve currency
- Classic, mutually self-reinforcing Big Cycle upswing

### American Golden Age (1945-1966)

- **Enough money for US to improve education, invent fabulous technologies (e.g., those that allowed it to go to the moon), and a lot more**
- **Stock market hit high in 1966, marked end of good times for 16 years, though nobody knew it then**
- Dalio started investing in 1961 at age 12, didn't know what he was doing, had no appreciation for how lucky contemporaries were
- Born at right time and place—US leading manufacturing country, labor was valuable
- Most adults could get good job, kids could get college education and rise without limitation
- Majority of people middle class, so majority happy

### US Banking Goes Global

- US did classic things that helped world become more dollarized
- Banks increased operations and lending in foreign markets
- 1965: only 13 US banks had foreign branches
- By 1970: 79 banks had them
- By 1980: nearly every major US bank had at least one foreign branch
- Total number of branches kept growing to 757
- Global lending boomed
- However, as typical: a) those who prospered overdid things by operating financially imprudently, b) global competition, especially from Germany and Japan, increased
- American lending and America's finances began to deteriorate as trade surpluses disappeared

### "Guns and Butter" Fiscal Policy

- **Americans never thought about how much space program, War on Poverty, and Vietnam War would cost**
- **Felt so rich and dollar seemed secure as reserve currency, assumed they could afford "guns and butter" fiscal policy indefinitely**
- By late 1960s: real GDP growth near 0%, inflation around 6%, short-term government interest rate around 8%, unemployment around 4%
- During decade, US stocks returned 8% annually while bonds trailed (equity-volatility-matched bonds returning -3% annually)
- Official gold price remained fixed in dollar terms with modest market price appreciation later in decade
- Commodities continued to be weak, returning 1% annually

## The 1970s: The Balance of Payments Problem Unfolds

### Understanding Claims on Money vs. Real Money

- When claims on hard money (notes or paper money) introduced, at first same number of claims as hard money in bank
- Holders of paper claims and banks soon discover wonders of credit and debt
- Debt holders like lending paper claims to bank for interest payment
- Banks like borrowing to lend to others at higher interest rate for profit
- Those who borrow from bank like it because gives buying power they didn't have
- Whole society likes it because asset prices and productivity rise

### The Classic Run on Gold (1945-1971)

- After 1945, foreign central banks had option of holding interest-rate-paying debt or non-interest-rate-earning gold
- Dollar-denominated debt considered as good as gold, convertible to gold, higher-earning because of provided interest
- Central banks shrank gold holdings relative to dollar-denominated debt holdings from 1945 until 1971
- **Classic behavior**: investors making such move ends when:
  - a) **Claims on real money (gold) substantially exceed amount of real money in bank**
  - b) **One can see amount of real money in bank (gold reserves) is going down**
- **When no interest rate can be high enough to make sense to hold debt rather than turn paper money in for gold**
- **At that time, run on bank occurs and default and debt restructuring have to happen**
- **This is what led to breakdown of gold-linked Bretton Woods monetary system**

### The Crisis of 1969-1971

- As inflation accelerated and economy weakened in 1969-70, Fed could not afford to maintain tight monetary policy
- US balance of payments worsened; dollar took nosedive
- Rather than running surpluses, US ran unsustainably huge balance of payments deficits (bought more from rest of world than sold to rest of world)
- Summer 1971: Americans traveling in Europe had difficulty exchanging dollars for German marks, French francs, British pounds
- **Nixon administration vowed not to "devalue" dollar, but in August 1971, US defaulted on commitments to pay in gold, offering paper money instead**
- Money and credit growth no longer constrained; decade of stagflation begun
- Other industrialized countries regained economic strength, becoming very competitive in world markets

### American Attitudes vs. Reality

- **Rather than seeing problems as signs of things to come, Americans viewed them as nothing more than temporary setback**
- **Yet as decade progressed, economic problems contributed to political problems and vice versa**
- Vietnam War and Watergate affair dragged on
- OPEC-induced oil price increases and drought-induced food price hikes
- Americans borrowed more to maintain lifestyles; Fed allowed accelerated money supply growth to accommodate high borrowing and prevent unacceptably high interest rates

### Petrodollar Recycling

- Dollars these deficits produced went to countries running budget surpluses, which deposited them in American banks
- Lent them to Latin American and other emerging, commodity-producing countries
- Savings and loan associations borrowed short to make longer-term mortgages and other loans
- Used positive spread between short rates (borrowed at) and long rates (lent at) as source of profits
- Inflation and effects on markets came in two big waves bracketed by periods of extreme monetary tightness, steep stock market declines, and deep recessions
- **Early in 1970s, most Americans had never experienced inflation, so weren't wary of it and allowed it to blossom**
- **By end of decade, traumatized by it and assumed would never go away**

### Economic Conditions by End of 1970s

- Real GDP growth around 2%
- Inflation around 14%
- Short-term interest rates around 13%
- Unemployment around 6%
- Over decade, gold surged and commodities kept up with rising inflation, returning around 30% and 15% on annualized basis
- High inflation rate wiped out modest 5% annual nominal return for stocks and 4% return for treasuries matched to equity volatility

## The Post-Bretton Woods System

### Transition to Fiat Money (Type 3)

- **After 1971 delinking of dollar and other currencies from gold, world moved to unanchored fiat monetary system (Type 3)**
- **Dollar fell in value against gold, other currencies, stocks, and eventually just about everything**
- New monetary system negotiated by leading economic policy makers of US, Germany, and Japan
- **Paul Volcker** was Nixon's undersecretary of international monetary affairs when Nixon severed link with gold
- Head of Federal Reserve from 1979 until 1987
- Did more to shape and guide dollar-based monetary system before, during, and after these years than anyone
- Dalio personally attests Volcker was person of great character, capabilities, influence, and humility
- Classic hero/role model in world that lacks hero/role models, especially in economic public service
- Deserves to be studied more

### The Inflation Psychology

- **Inflation psychology of that time led Americans to borrow money and immediately take paychecks to buy things to "get ahead of inflation"**
- They bought things that couldn't make more of, like gold and waterfront properties
- Panic out of dollar debt also led interest rates to rise and drove gold price from $35 (fixed at in 1944, officially stayed at until 1971) to $850 in 1980

### Social and Political Turmoil

- While most people didn't understand money and credit dynamic, felt pain in form of high inflation and high interest rates
- Chronic political issue
- Lot of conflict and rebellion due to:
  - War in Vietnam
  - Oil embargoes leading to high gas prices and gas rationing
  - Labor union fights with companies over wages and benefits
  - Watergate and Nixon impeachment
- Problems peaked in late 1970s when **52 Americans held hostage for 444 days at US Embassy in Tehran**
- Americans felt country was falling apart
- What most Americans didn't understand: **economic conditions in communist countries were even worse**

### China's Economic Transformation (1976-1978)

- **Mao Zedong's death in 1976 brought Deng Xiaoping to power in China that was stumbling economically and facing internal conflict**
- **Deng's market reforms led to shift in economic policies** that included:
  - **Capitalist elements like private ownership of businesses**
  - **Development of debt and equities markets**
  - **Entrepreneurial technological and commercial innovations**
  - **Flourishing of billionaire capitalists—all under strict control of Chinese Communist Party**
- **This shift in leadership and approaches, while seemingly insignificant at time, would germinate into biggest single force to shape 21st century**

## The 1979-1982 Move to Tight Money and Conservatism

### Volcker's Monetary Policy Shock

- **President Jimmy Carter** appointed strong monetary policy maker (**Volcker**) as head of Federal Reserve in August 1979
- October 1979: **Volcker announced he would constrain money (M1) growth at 5.5 percent**
- Dalio ran numbers, figured if Volcker really did what he said, would be great shortage of money
- Would send interest rates through roof, bankrupting debtors who couldn't get credit needed to cover debt-service expenses
- Volcker stuck to plan despite great political backlash
- Drove interest rates to highest levels seen "since Jesus Christ," according to German Chancellor **Helmut Schmidt**

### The Reagan Revolution

- **1980 presidential election: Carter voted out, Ronald Reagan elected**
- **Reagan perceived as conservative who would impose discipline where needed**
- **Leading countries at time (reflected in G7: US, UK, Germany, Japan, France, Italy, Canada) made analogous moves in electing conservatives to bring discipline to their inflationary chaos**
- Shows how different world power balance was 40 years ago versus today
- Early in terms, both Reagan in US and **Margaret Thatcher** in UK had landmark fights with labor unions

### Political and Economic Cycles

> "Economics and politics have swings between the left and the right in varying extremes as the excesses of each become intolerable and the memories of the problems of the other fade. It's like fashion—the widths of ties and the lengths of skirts change through time. When there is a great matter of one extreme, one should expect that it won't be too long before there will be a comparable move in the opposite direction."

- Move to monetary tightness broke backs of debtors and curtailed borrowing
- Drove world economy into worst downturn since Great Depression
- Federal Reserve slowly started to cut interest rates, but markets continued to decline
- Then **Mexico defaulted on its debt in August 1982**
- Interestingly, US stock market rallied in response

### Dalio's Personal Learning Experience (1982)

- Dalio able to anticipate debt crisis, profitable for him
- Also led him to:
  - a) Anticipate debt-default-triggered depression that never came
  - b) Lose a lot of money betting on it
- Result of personal losses and losses of clients: had to let everyone in fledgling company **Bridgewater Associates** go
- Was so broke had to borrow $4,000 from dad to help pay family's bills
- Same time, one of best things that ever happened because changed whole approach to decision making
- What Dalio missed: **when debts are in currencies that central banks have ability to print and restructure, debt crises can be well-managed so not systemically threatening**
- Federal Reserve could provide money to banks that made loans that weren't being paid back
- Banks didn't have cash flow problem
- American accounting system didn't require banks to account for bad debts as losses
- No big problem that couldn't be worked out
- Learned: **value of assets is reciprocal of value of money and credit (cheaper money and credit, more expensive asset prices) and value of money is reciprocal of quantity of it in existence, so when central banks producing lot of money and credit and making it cheaper, wise to be more aggressive in owning assets**

## The Disinflationary and Booming 1980s

- Stock market and economic boom accompanied by falling inflation and falling interest rates in United States
- Same time, inflationary depressions in debt-burdened emerging economies that didn't have ways to bail them out
- Debt-restructuring process progressed slowly from 1982 until 1989
- Agreement called **Brady Plan** (named after **Nicholas Brady**, US Treasury secretary) created, started to bring end to "lost decade" in these countries
- Agreements reached with different countries through early '90s
- **This whole 1971-91 up-and-down debt cycle profoundly affected just about everyone in world**
- **Was result of US going off gold standard, inflation that followed it, and having to break back of inflation through tight monetary policies that led to strength in dollar and dramatic fall in inflation**
- In markets, big cycle showed up via:
  - a) Soaring of inflation and inflation-hedge assets and bear markets in bonds in 1970s
  - b) 1979-81 bone-crushing monetary tightening that made cash best investment, led to lot of deflationary debt restructuring by non-American debtors
  - c) Falling inflation rates and excellent performance of bonds, stocks, and other disinflationary assets in 1980s
- Following charts convey this very well
- Show swings up and down in dollar-denominated inflation rates and interest rates from 1945 to present
- Need to keep these moves and mechanics behind them in mind when thinking about future

### Dollar's Continued Dominance

- Through it all, dollar remained world's leading reserve currency
- Entire period was forceful demonstration of benefits to US of having currency that most of world's debts are denominated in

## 1990-2008: Globalizing, Digitalizing, and Booming Financed by Debt

### Soviet Union Collapse and Globalization

- **Soviet Union could not afford to support: a) its empire, b) its economy, and c) its military in face of Reagan's arms-race spending**
- Soviet Union broke down in 1991
- Apparent that communism had failed or was failing everywhere
- Many countries moved away from it; world entered very prosperous period of globalization and free-market capitalism

### Three Economic Cycles (1990-2020)

- **Since then, three economic cycles have brought us to where we are at time of writing:**
  - **One that peaked in 2000 dot-com bubble, led to recession that followed**
  - **One that peaked in 2007 bubble, led to 2008 global financial crisis**
  - **One that peaked in 2019, just before 2020 coronavirus-triggered downturn**
- **In addition to decline of Soviet Union, period saw rise of China, globalization, and advances in technologies that replaced people, which was good for corporate profits but widened wealth and opportunity gaps**

### Globalization's Impact

- Countries and borders faded in importance
- Goods and incomes they produced generally made wherever could be most cost-effectively produced
- Led to production and development in emerging countries
- Accelerating mobility of people between countries, narrowing wealth gaps between countries, ballooning wealth gaps within them
- Lower- and middle-income workers in developed countries suffered
- Workers in productive emerging countries saw big relative gains
- **Bit of oversimplification, but accurate to say: this was period in which workers in other countries, especially those in China, and machines replaced middle-class workers in United States**

### US-China Trade Dynamics

- Following chart shows balances of goods and services for United States and China since 1990 in real (inflation-adjusted) dollars
- As will see when looking at China in next chapter:
  - **China's economic reforms and open-door policies after Deng Xiaoping came to power in 1978**
  - **China's being welcomed into World Trade Organization in 2001**
  - Led to explosion of Chinese competitiveness and exports
- Note accelerations in Chinese surpluses and US deficits from around 2000 to around 2010
- Then some narrowing of differences (recently ticked up during pandemic)
- China still tending to run surpluses; US still running deficits
- These surpluses have given China big savings that are great financial power

### Political Economy of Debt

> "Most people pay attention to what they get and not where the money comes from to pay for it, so there are strong motivations for elected officials to spend a lot of borrowed money and make a lot of promises to give voters what they want and to take on debt and non-debt liabilities that cause problems down the road."

- Certainly the case in 1990-2008 period

### The Long-Term Debt Cycle (1945-2008)

- Throughout long-term debt cycle from 1945 until 2008, whenever Federal Reserve wanted economy to pick up, would lower interest rates and make money and credit more available
- Would increase stock and bond prices and increase demand
- How it was done until 2008: interest rates cut, debts increased faster than incomes to create unsustainable bubbles
- Changed when bubble burst in 2008 and interest rates hit 0% for first time since Great Depression
- As explained in **Principles for Navigating Big Debt Crises**, three types of monetary policy:
  1. Interest-rate-driven monetary policy (**Monetary Policy 1**): first to be used, preferable way to run monetary policy
  2. Printing money and buying financial assets, most importantly bonds (**Monetary Policy 2**): now popularly called "quantitative easing"
  3. Coordination between fiscal policy and monetary policy where central government does lot of debt-financed spending and central bank buys that debt (**Monetary Policy 3**): third and last approach to be used when first two cease to be effective

### Transition to Money Printing (2008)

- Next charts show how debt crises of 1933 and 2008 both led to interest rates hitting 0% and were followed by big money printing by Federal Reserve
- Charts show private sector non-financial debt and interest rates/monetary base over time
- **This change in monetary policy had big effects and implications**

## The 2008-2020 Money-Financed Capitalist Boom

### New Era of Monetary Policy

- **In 2008 debt crisis led to interest rates being lowered until they hit 0 percent**
- Led three main reserve currency central banks (led by Fed) to move from interest-rate-driven monetary policy to monetary policy of printing money and buying financial assets
- Central banks printed money and bought financial assets, putting money in hands of investors who bought other financial assets
- Caused financial asset prices to rise
- Helpful for economy and particularly beneficial to those who were rich enough to own financial assets
- Increased wealth gap
- Basically, borrowed money essentially free
- Investment borrowers and corporate borrowers took advantage to get it and used it to make purchases that drove stock prices and corporate profits up
- Money did not trickle down proportionately
- Wealth and income gaps grew to largest since 1930-45 period

### Political Polarization and the Rise of Trump

- **In 2016, Donald Trump, blunt-speaking businessman and capitalist/populist of right, led revolt against establishment politicians and "elites" to get elected president by promising to support people with conservative values who had lost jobs and were struggling**
- Went on to cut corporate taxes and run big budget deficits that Fed accommodated
- While debt growth financed relatively strong market-economy growth and created some improvements for lower-income earners, accompanied by further widening of wealth and values gap
- Leading "have-nots" to become increasingly resentful of "haves"
- **At same time, political gap grew with increasingly extreme Republicans on one side and increasingly extreme Democrats on other**
- Reflected in next two charts
- First shows how conservative Republicans in Senate and House and how liberal Democrats in Senate and House have become relative to past
- Based on this measure, become more extreme, and divergence become larger than ever before
- While Dalio not sure that's exactly right, thinks it's by and large right

### Congressional Partisanship

- Next chart shows percentage of votes along party lines for average representative
- Highest ever
- Continues to be reflected in reduced willingness to cross party lines to compromise and reach agreements
- Political splits in country have become deep and intransigent

### Rising International Tensions

- **Trump took more aggressive negotiating posture concerning economic and geopolitical disagreements with international rivals, particularly China and Iran, and allies such as Europe and Japan regarding trade and paying for military expenditures**
- Conflicts with China over trade, technology, geopolitics, and capital were intensifying as his term ended in 2021
- Economic sanctions such as those used in 1930-45 period being used or put on table for possible use

